rater_role: Collaboratively between TL Staff/Coach and School/District Coaches/Leaders
fsot_ac1_notes: Siri was following the general pacing guide for Fundations; however, she did not implement with fidelity. She was going through all the letters of the alphabet for letter-keyword-sound practice and she did not review the vowels.
fsot_td_notes:
Siri started off on the right track for modeling, "Ms. Siri says it first, then you say it..." However, as the lesson carried on, there wasn't a clear distinction of when it was her turn to model and students' turn to practice. She also incorrectly said /b/ by adding a vowel at the end. She lacked a clear cue for when students should practice or say the letter-keyword-sound. 

Siri was not previously trained in Fundations, and as a result of going through sequential letters of the alphabet, the lesson was dragged. 

Siri exhibited a smile and warm demeanor while also having several moments praising/recognition student participation. However, the skills taught were not practiced through movement, songs, chants, or high-energy activities.
fsot_sp_notes:
While the letter sound cards aligned with the letter sounds, there lacked a reinforcement of critical sounds that should be practiced according to Fundations daily: vowels and new letters introduced. 

Students, because they lacked a strong model, did not all get a chance to practice the sounds with multiple opportunities. Most students were not actively participating and were not held accountable either (1-3 out of 6 kids at every instance of practice).

fsot_ac1_notes: Ms. Bell had her LP in hand with materials prepped that aligned to the pacing schedule.
fsot_td_notes:
While Ms. Bell was prepared, she focused on getting through the lesson as opposed to students engaged and participating. To that end, her model was missing and she asked the students to name the letter, keyword and sounds and then didn't stamp with a model either. 

She did narrate how she was writing the letters, but she was blocking the board most kids were not participating. 

The lesson was too long because of many moments of interruption the need for student redirection. 

She did have a visual easel posted for kids to  see. 

She did not present the content in an engaging work.
fsot_sp_notes:
At the most, 4-5 students were participating the entire time out of a class of 20+ kids. 

She lacked clear clears for students to participate. She didn't clarify the expectations on the front end for what kids are supposed to do and how they do it.  So her directions were either missing or unclear.

teacher: Ms. Wendy Hamilton and Ms. Noelle Stella
fsot_targeted_skills: Letter-Keyword-Sound practice; Vowel Practice with chart
fsot_ac1_notes: It was clear they were following the pacing schedule but some of the components took longer to implement and lacked fidelity overall.
fsot_td_notes:
It was clear both teachers were following some pacing guide for Fundations that the leadership team established from the beginning. 

There were moments of a clear model. Teachers also used language to be explicit and clear about their model, "Make sure your teether are..." and "Tongues touches the roof of your mouth..." 

There were moments when the teacher (Noelle) said, "Let me hear it again" but didn't make the correction for what she wanted to hear better this time and she said the letter-keyword-sound with them so it became confusing. Hamilton did make sure to reset in some moments to clarify the lines of who is going to model and when it was students' turn. She brightened the lines a little better.

Q143: How to develop a character in a narrative
Q150:
The expectation of sharing and contributing is there. They are very present and contribute. I think we will see whether they complete things that are difficult for them. The growth journal was an example of something that might be difficult for them and they were not too engaged in. I noticed one member in particular, Avalon, having a hard time. 

A suggestion for moving forward with this and with the growth journal. 1. Tie the growth journal to what they are doing in some way- like, the journal is documentation on their character development and to be a good writer, they have to know themselves and talk about themselves so they can better understand others. Writing is a vulnerable process and a lot of yourself comes out in it. 
2. When you give them time to write, make sure they are writing. Go around the room and ask them to share the answer to the question out loud and then write it down. Avalon seems like someone who likes to process verbally first.
Q159:
All students seemed to be pretty similar. Very knowledgeable about pop culture, have watched a lot of movies, have thought about the themes in the class at least once before, seem to have these types of conversations with friends. I am wondering how other folks who might not fit that mold feel in the setting, especially because folks seem to be comfortable sharing their ideas out loud. 

They seemed to be very engaged with the content and they all understand it.
Q166:
The individual module is structured in a good way. I think each topic built on each other and increased in complexity. I will follow up on whether I think the whole series can be structured differently. This will depend on the deliverables from the members.

k12_m_learning_goal:
Calculate the volume of prisms.
Solve problems involving calculating the volume of prisms.
Calculate the volume of figures composed of prisms.
k12_m_standards:
CC.5.MD.3: Recognize volume as an attribute of solid figures.and understand concepts of volume measurement. A: a cube with side length 1 unit, called a “unit cube” has a volume of “one cubic unit” of volume and can be used to measure volume.B: A solid figure which can be packed without gaps or overlaps using n unit cubes is said to have a volume of n cubic units.

CC.5.MD.4: Measure volume by counting unit cubes, using cubic cm, cubic in, cubic ft, and improvised units

CC.5.MD.5: Relate volume to the operations of multiplication and addition and solve real world and mathematical problems involving volume.
CC.5.MD.5.a: Find the volume of a right rectangular prism with whole number side lengths by packing it with unit cubes, and show that the volume is the same as would be found by multiplying the edge lengths, equivalently by multiplying the height by the area of the base. Represent threefold whole number products as volumes e.g. to represent the associative property of multiplication.

CC.5.MD.5.b: Apply the formulas A = l*w*h and V = B*h for rectangular prisms to find volumes of right rectangular prisms with whole number edge lengths in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

CC.5.MD.5.c: Recognize volume as additive. Find volumes of figures composed of two non-overlapping right rectangular prisms by adding the volumes of the non-overlapping parts, applying this technique to solve real world problems.

CC.6.G.2: Find the volume of a right rectangular prism with fractional edge lengths by packing it with unit cubes of the appropriate unit fraction edge lengths, and show that the volume is the same as would be found by multiplying the edge lengths of the prism. Apply the formulas V = l*w*h and V = B*h to find volumes of right rectangular prisms with fractional edge lengths in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.

fsot_ac1_notes:
Teacher is providing context in building student knowledge that will lead to final assessment around whole class and partner discussion around toy selection. Teacher wanted to demonstrate crafts that can be created around toilet paper and provided a few visual examples. Teacher read a book on the toys the main character loves.

Teacher could have also introduced print concepts aligned with the toy examples for the early readers as well. Additionally, providing 1 min Turn and talk to share what each student would want to make would stimulate creative thinking. 

Additionally, teacher could have built in a quick check for understanding before setting students off to work independently to identify which students needed additional targeted support.

Digital Visuals were great, but live model showcasing materials used on pictures (with printed words labeling materials) would have further helped build in word recognition for students and even additional practice of writing the word for the higher third in the class.
fsot_td_notes: There was enough time built in for the activity. Teacher could have made the lesson more engaging based on notes above. Additionally, she could have also shortened the students time on the rug so they have more time to interact with the activity

fsot_ac1_notes: Students were exposed to the text of "the Magnificent Thing" for the 2nd day in a row. Today was a recording of the reading and book played on the SmartBoard. Teacher asked text related questions focusing on steps of the magnificent thing. Students excited to participate and share.
fsot_td_notes:
Build in a purposeful Turn and talk to allow students to make a clear connection to the foundational skills based on the reading/listening. This will allow the students who were eager to share a chance to participate and began calling out. It's also a way to get more voices heard that were not participating. 

A lot of teacher to student directed questioning - students need to carry more of the cognitive load (there was half engagement and half disengaged). Building in deliberate turn and talks and gathering data will allow teacher to assess and gather data that will help them make real time adjustments if/when needed. This will also help students practice using oral skills that are aligned to targeted content.

Students were exposed to text, but did not observe students reading or decoding texts either independently or within groups.

k12_ela_ca1a: No- There is no text under consideration in this lesson.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: The focal task for students was to input information into an electronic graphic organizer in order to learn about an important cultural figure of their choosing. The graphic organizer included a column for a website, a column for the main idea presumably from the content of the webpage, and "key facts or quotations." The teacher began the class by showing students how to copy and paste a web address onto the graphic organizer. The teacher spoke in an uncomfortably loud voice when speaking to the whole class. It's not clear how well students were reading and thinking about the text they were selecting from the websites. Multiple students clicked on the first website that appeared in a Google search. Students tended to copy and paste web addresses for Britannica and Wikipedia.
k12_ela_ca2a: 2- Few questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 2- Few questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 1- No questions and tasks focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 2- Few questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: Many students cut and paste quotations into the graphic organizer. There was little to no original writing about either the meaning of those quotations, key facts, or main ideas. Ostensibly, the graphic organizer solicited main idea and detail formulation, but the observed activity included cutting and pasting websites and quotations without short or extended student written response. Two students asked for assistance, and said, "We don't know what this means" (pointing to question #4 on a document meant to be completed after the graphic organizer in preparation for a presentation on a notable cultural figure). The question seemed to be asking students to interpret how the person's culture and identity influenced their music, art, or other creative output, but I also found the wording to be unclear.

k12_ela_ca3_notes: Multiple students frequently engaged in off task conversations and behaviors. One student walked around the room, placed pen ink cartridges into water bottles, and did not open a laptop for most of the lesson. The teacher did not intervene until 40 minutes into the lesson when she said, "S, you seem distracted today," but there was no other observable follow up. Four students sat at a separate table to complete an IXL diagnostic, but they exhibited frequent and extended off task talk and behavior within and beyond their group. I did observe the teacher assisting students with technical issues related to copying and pasting content. I did not observe the teacher in a brief or sustained conversation with any students about what they were reading, discovering, or writing about. In a very loud voice, the teacher did ask the whole class why citing a source was important, and one student responded that it was like "backing something up." The teacher affirmed this and insisted students find another source to back up anything they found on Wikipedia.

fsot_targeted_skills: I can read words with the short a sound.
fsot_ac1_notes: Students showed familiarity with routines while sitting on the rug and engaging in call and response as well as choral pronunciation exercises. Students also showed familiarity with routines for student work at their table, for how to ask for help, and for turning practice work in and demonstrating pre-reading and early reading to the teacher. The room was organized with many literacy focused and supportive tools, artifacts, messages, and other representations. The content was part of Skyline.
fsot_td_notes:
Teacher began with review of words rhyming with "did," and asked students for examples. She then led students on an activity to repeat beginning sounds. After this, she told students they would be blending, and the students clapped together over their heads, indicating their familiarity with the gesture in relation to the term. Teacher periodically reminded students by saying, "S, and S, it's important that we all participate. I want to hear your voices. The teacher then moved on to emphasizing beginning and ending sounds. Students orally emphasized phonemes with teacher. Teacher then moved to segmenting sounds and students again orally emphasized the beginning and ending sounds of words (e.g. at, my, tie, be). 

Also at the rug, the teacher showed letter cards (e.g., J, Z, T, V) in succession to students, and together they said the letter and then the sound. With the letter "I" students' articulation was unclear. Teacher smoothly said, "Wait, what is this one again?" and provided corrected pronunciation. Later, after repetition reading of a short passage, when students jumbled the final sentence, the teacher again paused and said, "Let's try that again with, 'The Gingerbread men all ran away." 

Introducing the focal lesson content, the teacher directed students to segment "sat," "sad," "hat" and other short a cvc words. Then she guided students in singing along with a video on cvc words with short a sound. Most students articulated the target sounds clearly. It was unclear if one student sitting closest to the screen was speaking. When teacher led students in segmenting first the letters and then the sounds of "tap, pan, man, etc..." she used visual slides and gestures deliberately. There was broad participation and the pace included clear articulations from all students. Here again, the teacher quickly corrected a student's "r" sound for the word "bag" and the student successfully redid it. 

It was unclear how many students were participating in the "Learning letters from A to Z" video, and the teacher did intervene with two separate children multiple times for disruptive behavior during the teacher directed time.
fsot_sp_notes: At their table groups, each student worked in their own 9-square handout with nine 3-letter short a sound words. Their task was to read the word and draw a picture of it in the square above the word. Students were instructed to color in their pictures and then share their completed sheets with the teacher. Most students diligently set to work, and most frequently raised a hand to request for help from the teacher, either of two additional educational professionals, and me. Most students, with varying degrees of assistance were able to read and draw a picture of all nine words by 75 minutes into the overall lesson (though student practice was only a portion of this).
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher and teacher aids assisted students by offering a next step of assistance, and relying on the student to take the step and attempt to segment the letter sounds and then put them together and then read the word and then, sometimes, say what the word means. Most students completed their own drawings. When a student turned in a handout, the teacher had the student read aloud to her each of the nine words in turn, and the teacher provided corrections or hints when detecting errors.

k12_ela_ca2_notes: Teacher engaged in vocabulary pre-work with students by having them record words (3) in their notebooks including definitions. Teacher then had each student access the historical article in their Google classroom.  Students were paired with partners.  Teacher employed gradual release of responsibility with reading by alternating between her reading aloud and partner pairs taking turns regarding assigned paragraphs.  Teacher would strategically stop at the end of each paragraph to ask probing and clarifying questions to further deepen students understanding of the content. Teacher consistently followed this format throughout the duration of the lesson. Teacher also integrated a video that spoke on various types of text structures (description, sequence, cause and effect, compare and contrast, and problem and solution). She strategically stopped video after each term to provide check for students' understanding through questioning and building on prior knowledge. After the video, teacher returns to historical article read and asks students to identify the text structure of the article. She surveys each student for an answer based on the text structures they learned; however, all responses were verbal.

2. Extension Lessons for Emergent Bilingual students
k12_ela_lg:
1. I can write compliments and suggestions about my peers' thematic essay final draft.
2. I can explore a non-fiction text to identify similarities and differences between topics.
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: Initially in the lesson, each student read a peer's thematic essay about the text A Long Walk to Water. As instructed, each student wrote a compliment on a sticky note. Each student moved to another peer's laptop and repeated this. Then, a student volunteered to read aloud his last paragraph and the compliments he received from peers. After that, students quizzed each other at their tables on a vocabulary sheet. The took turns verbally identifying the Spanish language term for the given English vocabulary term. Following this brief transition activity, the teacher first modeled and then students independently practiced using a venn diagram with a Spanish language New York Times news article about water issues in Mexico. Their task was to compare and contrast, using the diagram, water in South Sudan (the setting for A Long Walk to Water), and water in Mexico. Most students independently read, or read and watched an accompanying video, and completed a Venn diagram.
k12_ela_ca2a: 4- Most questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 4- Most questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 4- Vocabulary questions and tasks consistently focus students on the words, phrases, and sentences that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 4- Most questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: When the teacher modeled the construction of the Venn diagram, he deliberated modeled ways to fix up and change entries to the diagram, and he did so interactively by inviting student input. For example, he first put a student entry in the middle, and then he asked questions about it, and then moved it under the section for South Sudan and then helped students construct a counterpart under the section for Mexico, modeling how to think about what is similar and what is different and what the texts support. He also emphasized and probed to discover if students understood what it meant to identify similarities and differences. During this, he pointed out that El aqua es limpia should be changed to El aqua es limpio. Then, when a student suggested it, he incorporated "mas" to create "El aqua es mas limpio."

k12_ela_ca3_notes: Students read and wrote in response to their peers' essays without the teacher reminding them how to proceed after first explaining the goal and activity. Later, students worked in groups to quiz one another. After that, students used over 15 minutes to read the non-fiction text and/or listen to the video and fill in a Venn diagram. Throughout each lesson component, the teacher offered one-on-one assistance for 10 seconds to 3 minutes to individual students around the room at their tables. In one instance, he read aloud part of the Spanish language passage and asked the student what she thought about it. The student then entered text into her Venn diagram.

k12_ela_lg:
1. I can evaluate my progress on the learning standards.
2. I can compare and contrast themes of texts.
3. I can use text evidence to support my written analysis.
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.

k12_ela_ca1_notes: The teacher started the lesson by having students read aloud the "I can" statements of the lesson objectives. She invited students to elaborate on the meanings of those sections  and define terms (e.g. "relevant"). Several students shared. The teacher then introduced the core lesson activity with the Skyline texts: The Smoking Mirror plus one other text of students' choosing from Unit 1 or Unit 2. The task was to use the content in their graphic organizers to write extended literary responses that explore how their own generated theme in each text and connected theme across texts is represented in the texts. The teacher showed students where they can find their already completed theme and text evidence in Google Classroom, and invited students to identify which resources they can use. Students offered, "themes anchor chart," "hero's journey note catcher," "personal themes planners," "summaries," and "the texts." The teacher shared her own example of a theme across texts as "supernatural powers help heroes achieve the impossible," and emphasizes that students' own themes can be and should be different from her example.
k12_ela_ca2a: 3- Many questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 3- Many questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 3- Vocabulary questions and tasks mostly focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 4- Most questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: It took approximately 40 minutes for students to begin working independently on their writing task using their various resources. The preceding 40 minutes included the teacher introducing the tasks, inviting student responses, and frequent stops and starts to address off task talk and behavior. When the students did begin work, more than half of the students began writing their themes into the day's organizer. Several students raised hands to ask clarifying questions. Several students continued with off task behavior. The teacher and I both moved about the room to assist students with their questions. The teacher responded directly, warmly, and briefly to each student she spoke with and moved on to another student.

k12_ela_ca3_notes: The teacher used Skyline materials in ways consistent with their intended use. As an observer, it was clear to me what the student task was, what resources they had, where students could locate them. Most students began working earnestly as soon as student practice began. That said, several students asked questions that indicated they were either uncertain about the directions or still putting together what counts as a theme within each text or across both texts. The teacher spent the first two thirds of the class session introducing the task and trying to manage students' off task behavior and talk. Because of this, students ended up with less time to actually work on the task than they needed to make substantial progress during that day's session.

k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: Although not a Skyline text, Restart by Gordon Korman is an appropriate and potentially powerful text for fifth graders.
k12_ela_ca2a: 3- Many questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 3- Many questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 3- Vocabulary questions and tasks mostly focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 3- Some questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes:
The lesson began with a warm up exercise directing students to view the picture on on the screen and "Make as many inferences as you can about this picture. Write complete sentences." Students wrote sentences in their notebook as both the teacher and SECA circulated the room to read and initial students' responses. To one student, the teacher said, "Tell me what you see," followed by, "What else?" 

After the warm up, the T displayed a matrix of four groups and three rotations for literacy centers. [Round 1: IXL, Teacher table, SECA table
Round 2: Independent reading, SECA table
Round 3: Independent reading, Teacher table, SECA table]
The screen displayed a 15 minute countdown clock for each round. 

Round 1: After several minutes of noisy transition, 6 students and the T were seated at the kidney table. Another 5 students were seated around a table with the SECA, and approximately 10 students were working either independently or in pairs on IXL on laptops. 
At the T table, all 6 students have their copies of "Restart" open and a Restart packet and pencil on the table in front of them. One student begins reading from the start of chapter 7. After the student read a paragraph or two, the T asked, "What do you think Shoshawna is feeling and why?" A couple students responded. One student said, "Wait, what? What happened?" The T asked another student to recap the previous chapter and then invited other students to clarify who characters are and their relationships. The student who expressed confusion said, "Okay." A different student reads the next paragraph or two. The T invites students to pause and answer a question about why a character is reacting a certain way. Students comment and the teacher then builds on the comments. She then directs them to go back to a sentence and the word, "dubiously." She asks them to try to figure out what it means from the context. Students offer, "unsure," and, "questioning." The teacher says she wants to check to be sure, uses her laptop quickly, and then says, "Right, so it means unsure, not believing, and not quite for real." She directs them to add to their vocab words. Students write. A student reads another paragraph and then the teacher says, "lets go back to the words and think about their meaning, 'defiant...discontent...filled with rage...the atmosphere feels supercharged,' and she invites students to explain what the effect of those words are. 
Similar interactions to the 1st round happen during the 3rd round. 
During the second round, the T circulates to check in with students as they begin independent reading. When I asked the teacher how the students were doing with their independent reading selections, the T replied that most are making good choices, and she intentionally checks in with students who need more assistance. Transitions between rounds take multiple minutes for several students.

With 15 minute rounds and at least a couple of minutes lost during transition for many students, the students do not read more than a couple of pages in the text Restart during guided reading. The questions they respond to are mostly about the plot and, when inferential, about the characters' feelings or thoughts or behaviors. Students tended to respond directly to the teacher and not to one another. 
The teacher later told me she was able to purchase the Restart packet from Amazon to go with the book. The packet included sections such as: graphic organizers to define preselected vocabulary terms in order by chapter, vocabulary and grammar practice examples by chapter, as well as text-dependent questions by chapter for multi-sentence written responses and directions to use textual evidence.

k12_ela_ca2_notes: The teacher introduced the read aloud mini lesson by asking, "Why do we have an Essential Question? What is that supposed to help us with?" A student replied, "It's important." Another student replied, "It helps you focus on what to learn." The teacher introduced the text "The Youngest Marcher" as "a true story based on a girl named Audre May Hendricks." She replied to several students questions and comments about true stories. She then read the learning targets for the lesson. After that, she engaged the class in pre-reading vocabulary building, using the Skyline Slates. She asked students for their ideas for the meanings of the words, one at a time, and she elaborated and clarified meanings for "civil rights, activist, overcome, stewed, segregation." Then she led a previewing conversation with the class about what they noticed and thought about the book cover picture. After that, she began to read aloud the text, pausing to check on student understanding, inviting them to recall vocab terms, and responding to student's comments and questions about characters in the text, including Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.

During the first part of the lesson, the students continued work on their graphic organizers to help them plan for writing a personal story. The graphic organizer included spaces for, "character(s), setting, the "challenge or problem," 3 events, solution, and ending." The teacher walked around the room and conferred with students as they worked on their organizers (different students had different amounts of their organizers completed and with different degrees of writing production). The teacher asked one student, "Okay, tell me about your story idea." The student replied, "I played soccer every day." The teacher said, "So then the challenge is playing soccer. What about soccer is challenging?" The student replied, "scoring a goal." And the teacher replied, "Okay, scoring a goal while playing soccer is the challenge." The student started to write that in his organizer. The teacher continued to assist students. 
During the second part of the lesson, the teacher repeatedly turned students to the meanings of the words in the text and to listen to each other's explanations of "segregation" and of "civil rights" and additional examples as students raised questions during the read aloud.

The teacher asked students, "According to the text, why did Abraham Lincoln grow a beard?" She called on a student who shared, "an eleven year old girl told him he would look more like a president." The teacher asked her where that appeared in the text. The student identified a page number. The teacher modeled how to complete that part of the handout on cause and effect. She directed a student to start reading part of chapter 6. She asked students what "seceded" means. A student answered. Then she projected a National Geographic map of the Union and Confederate states during the Civil War and engaged students in brief question and answer to activate and build background knowledge. She directed students to continue working on the handout. The teacher circulated the room to check in with students.

k12_ela/literacy_1: Challenges that animals in the city face and how they face them
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: The teacher read aloud from and the students subsequently drew evidence from the National Geographic (Reading Level 2) text "Animals in the City."
k12_ela_ca2a: 4- Most questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 3- Many questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 3- Vocabulary questions and tasks mostly focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 4- Most questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes:
With students sitting quietly on the rug, the teacher engaged students in pre-reading questions such as, "What is the animal on the cover?" and "What is the word for an animal that eats dead animals and trash to survive?" A student answered, "scavenger." The teacher directed student attention to the large chart paper on the wall with vocab terms (scavenger, predator, habitat, etc...). Teacher directed students to page 4 and asked if the picture was of an urban, suburban, or rural area. She emphasized, "animals are everywhere." 

Students began reading aloud on page 6. Students took turn reading 1-2 sentences. Then, the teacher would interject some comments or questions and then invite a different student to read aloud. In total, 9 different students read a passage or answered a question during the interactive and shared read aloud.
k12_ela_ca3a: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.

k12_ela_ca3f: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.
k12_ela_ca3_notes:
During the read aloud portion of the lesson, when students made pronunciation errors, the teacher corrected them in the moment and then the student repeated the word correctly without slowing down (e.g. "starts" instead of "struts," and "bites," instead of "bits," "choose" instead of "choice," "hiding" instead of "hidden," and "is" instead of "it's") In addition, the teacher directed students to turn and talk 3 times during the read aloud in response to questions such as, "What do you see pigeons doing in the city?" and "How do you think the animals feel when they lose their habitat when humans cut down their trees and build on their land?" Each time, students spoke with a neighbor, and each time, students linked hands and raised them up in the air together to indicate they were done and ready to share or move on.  

When students moved back to their table seats with a columned piece of paper for "animal," "challenge," and "facts," they wrote and referred to the same text. Many students raised hands for help, saying, "I don't know the challenge," or "The book doesn't say," but the teacher provided suggestions and hints such as, "Do pigeons have to find food? That's a challenge. Where do they find food? That's how they overcome their challenge. What's that kind of animal called? A scavenger. That's a fact about pigeons."

k12_m_learning_goal:
Use strategies to multiply and divide within 100.
Estimate the mass of objects using standard units.
k12_m_standards:
AR.Math.Content.3.OA.B.5 Apply properties of operations as strategies to multiply and divide For example: If 6 × 4 = 24 is known, then 4 × 6 = 24 is also known (Commutative property of multiplication). 3 × 5 × 2 can be found by 3 × 5 = 15, then 15 × 2 = 30, or by 5 × 2 = 10, then 3 × 10 = 30 (Associative property of multiplication). Knowing that 8 × 5 = 40 and 8 × 2 = 16, one can find 8 × 7 as 8 × (5 + 2) = (8 × 5) + (8 × 2) = 40 + 16 = 56 (Distributive property). Note: Students are not required to use formal terms for these properties. 
AR.Math.Content.3.OA.B.6 Understand division as an unknown-factor problem
AR.Math.Content.3.MD.A.2 • Measure and estimate liquid volumes and masses of objects using standard units such as: grams (g), kilograms (kg), liters (l), gallons (gal), quarts (qt), pints (pt), and cups (c) • Add, subtract, multiply, or divide to solve one-step word problems involving masses or volumes that are given in the same units (e.g., by using drawings (such as a beaker with a measurement scale) to represent the problem)

Rather than allowing students to determine which property or strategy should be used, he tells students to draw an array for numbers 4 - 6 and do what is in parentheses first, rather than allowing them to apply the distributive property. During the core activity, measurements are read to students and they do not have the opportunity to estimate using the scale.

Instead, he calls off the measurements from the scale and allows another student to provide the answer.

k12_ela_lg:
I can write a summary of "Nana Miriam."
I can determine themes and how they are conveyed in "Nana Miriam."
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: For this lesson, students participated by discussing elements of culture and their importance, completing a entry ticket handout about cultural practices, reviewing steps for annotation and notetaking, and then beginning to independently read and annotate the Skyline short story text, "Nana Miriam."
k12_ela_ca2a: 4- Most questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 3- Many questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 3- Vocabulary questions and tasks mostly focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 4- Most questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: As a pre-reading activity, the teacher asked students, "What makes up culture? What elements make up culture?" Individual students replied the following: "beliefs, language, art, religion, clothing, food, social structure, location, and music." The teacher used Skyline slates, and asked, "What elements of culture do you see in this picture?" Students identified, "music, clothing, jewelry/art, socializing, location [West Africa]". They watched part of a video on West African music with a lot of percussion, and a speaker talking about the history of the drums and the middle passage and the survival of the music and resilience of enslaved people from West Africa. The teacher and students discussed why it is important that cultural traditions are shared, with an emphasis on the shared aspect, but it wasn't clear what students understood about the role of sharing in cultural practices.

She asked a student questions about her family's traditions around this time of year to push her to write a specific example. After students completed entry ticket, the teacher handed out the "Nana Miriam" text and reviewed the annotation instructions by referring to the anchor chart in the room. She indicated students should annotate on every page. They should circle any unfamiliar words; underline important parts, new information, or places to make a connection; and then only when finished with the whole story should they create a chart on the back page of Who, what, why, so then..., and a summary. Students began reading the text independently.

Questions are posed that require students to determine who the story is about as well as what happened first, second and last. When students struggle to provide evidence for their responses, the teacher sends them to the part of the text where the answer can be found and sometimes to the exact sentence. When students do respond, they are not required to cite specific evidence (lines, words, phrases) to support their thinking or go beyond their initial thoughts. There is shared reading, but students do not discuss each others' thinking (until the TL coach asks them to share in their groups). Most students do not engage in the reading (until the TL coach asks them to finger track along with their peers). Students are noticeably confused, but there are no adjustment (e.g., chunking text, deliberate annotation) so that all can engage. Checks for understanding do occur at the end of the reading but not for the purpose of refining or improving their responses - more so for the correction of answers as this is a review of work previously submitted.

k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: The core text for this lesson is an 11 minute podcast from NPR about Ida B. Wells.
k12_ela_ca2a: 3- Many questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 3- Many questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 4- Most questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: At the start of the lesson, the students were sitting on the rug, the teacher projected an image of a KWL chart, and showed students the student-facing handout. He told them they would be listening to a podcast about Ida B. Wells and that her great grand daughter would be speaking on the podcast. Teacher referred to the K in the chart, "What do you KNOW about Ida B. Wells? We've been reading and talking about her for a week. Turn and talk to your partner." Students then moved to their table groups. The whole class of approximately 20 students wrote in the K and W sections. A few wrote multiple sentences in each. Several students asked for help spelling words. The teacher circulated and assisted students. At the end of this segment, a few students had only 1 entry in K or 1 entry in both K and W, even with assistance, while most other students had more than 1. The teacher directed students to return to the rug. The transition took under 10 seconds. The teacher directed students to turn and talk a second time to share their WONDER with a partner. The teacher then invited 3 students to share a WONDER with the whole class. At tables, students found the podcast in Google Classroom and began listening. The teacher circulated to encourage students to write in the LEARN column as they listened, and he celebrated their responses with "I love it!" "What else did you learn?" "Look at you, so much writing!" and "Write something new." After 15 minutes, students returned to the rug. The teacher had them turn and talk to share a LEARN with a partner.

k12_ela/literacy_1: 7.1a Lesson 10: A Long Walk to Water and "Conflict between Dinka and Nuer in South Sudan"
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: In this lesson, the class read aloud chapter 10 of "A Long Walk to Water," and then completed both a brief written summary and a note catcher inviting intertextual writing.
k12_ela_ca2a: 4- Most questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 4- Most questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 4- Most questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes:
At the start of the lesson, a student read aloud a 1-2 sentence summary from her Chapter Grid for chapter 8 of "A Long Walk to Water." Then another student read a summary from her Chapter Grid for chapter 9. The teacher began the whole class in a read aloud of chapter 10 by calling on a student. This third student read a couple pages. Afterwards, the teacher reread the final sentence and elaborated on the plot elements. Then, a fourth student read a couple of pages. Following this, the teacher took a turn reading and finished the chapter. The teacher then directed students to write their own summaries of the chapter in their chapter grids. The teacher said, "We can figure this out together by sharing ideas. Who has a summary idea?" A student shared. The teacher reiterated that the group was robbed. Then the teacher asked, "What happened to uncle?" A student said, "He was shot 3 times." "Right," said the Teacher, "he was shot. The group was robbed and uncle was shot. At the end of the chapter, we don't yet know if he is dead or alive. But earlier, we read that uncle had a plan for Salva. Did Salva accept that plan?" Some students say no. "That's right," said the teacher, "he is still hoping to see his family again." 
The teacher directs students to distribute the note catcher, and two students hand out a version of the chapter 10 note catcher with teacher created examples for situation 1. She goes over the note catcher and directs students to work independently or quietly with a table peer to complete the note catcher for a second situation. After approximately 10 minutes, the teacher projects the note catcher on the screen and informs students to be ready to share and to "pay attention if your boxes are blank. You were supposed to be working on this. You will need to turn it in."

k12_ela_ca3_notes: The teacher invites a student to share an example. The student reads her example. The teacher types for all to see, "On page 62, the men who robbed Salva and his Uncle were from the Nuer tribe (ritual scarring on one's face). and "On page 63, Salva saw one of the men aim his gun at his uncle and shoot 3 times." / Then the student shared more, and the teacher wrote, "In excerpt 2, traditional conflicts between the Dinka and Nuer have also been exacerbated by the civil war in Sudan. The war brought large quantities of heavy weapons." T asked, did the author Linda Sue Park use history or alter history? A student answered, "She used history." With some back and forth between teacher and student, the teacher typed the gist of the student's response as, "The reason why those men from the Nuer tribe shot Salva's uncle was because he was from the Dinka tribe." Anyone have a different example? After a brief second student sharing, the lesson ends as the teacher tells students to turn in their work and prepare to go to lunch.

k12_ela_ca1_notes: The anchor text used in this lesson was Plant to Seed; however, it was not the prescribed text for this lesson as noted in the TFG.  The book should have been Animal Defenses: How Animals Protect Themselves by Etta Kaner.  Teacher noted that she did not have the text and opted to reread Plant to Seed instead.

k12_ela_ca2_notes: Since the teacher did not use the anchor text as prescribed for this lesson, the teacher reread a text on plant survival and protection instead.  The teacher asked low-level questions about plants as she conducted the read aloud; however, the performance writing task she asked students to complete regarding animal defenses did not align with the information they received from the text given it was on the topic of plants.  Teacher tried to make a connection between the plant book and the topic students would be writing about by asking how do animals help plants move but no other connections were made.

fsot_ad_notes: The teacher did not assess students during the lesson.  She circulated and monitored students to ensure they could access the tasks in Google classroom, but did not record any data on students' ability to identify and read long vowel e words during the lesson.

k12_m_ca1_notes: This was the first lesson of a unit. The purpose of this lesson is for students to apply what they have learned about proportional relationships to describing geometric figures. The work in this lesson focuses on squares. In the first activity, students see that there is a proportional relationship between the length of the diagonal and the perimeter for squares of different sizes. They use a graph and a table to estimate the constant of proportionality and recognize that measurement error means they can only find an approximate value. This prepares students for future lessons when they will explore the relationship between diameter and circumference of circles. Although all students were able to measure their assigned squares, and began plotting on the graph there was not a clear point made about proportionality and marginal error.

Student Discussion: After students are given silent time to process to do now, the teacher advises students to discuss their responses in small groups. He reminds them, “You guys are not talking to me. I am just listening. Right now, you are talking and discussing in your groups, then we will share.” As he walks around to hear their discussion, he encourages students to explain in depth, asking them“How are they alike?” and “How are they different?”
Students collaborate to discuss solution methods to (16.3 Greatest Common Factor), saying phrases like “We need to know how many squares we need to take…” “The bulletin board is 12 inches tall and 27 inches wide, so we need to find the volume.”
Students are tasked with another Turn & Talk: “What is the relationship between multiples and factors?” Students use diagrams and their notes to discuss this. 

Productive Struggle: The teacher encourages students to productively struggle by offering guiding questions without explicitly explaining steps. “Could these be pieces of a puzzle?” Additionally, the teacher gives students time to connect the arithmetic to the real-world application, without interruption “I like that you guys are thinking.”

Practicing Grade-Level Content: Students are given time to work independently on multiple tasks; the do now, guided practice, independent practice, and an exit ticket. All questions are from the corresponding IM lesson: Grade 6, Unit 7, Lesson 16. 

Mathematical Langauge: The teacher encourages students to use mathematical language throughout his dialogue with them, “factors”, “let’s use greatest common fact instead of GCF”, “divisor,” etc.

Examples in class are lead exclusively by teacher. Processes are demonstrated (here, proportions to scale down to the unit rate) but no student-generated work is used to highlight or connection processes together.

k12_m_ca2_notes:
Teacher modeled (as review) for students how to use an Area Model to expand/factor expressions. Teacher did not ask that students apply the strategy on their own to check for understanding. Students then went directly into partner-work. 

No student solutions were shared via document camera, though students were asked to share the method they used orally to the whole class for the opening problem. 

Teacher circulated throughout opening problem and asked students "what next." During partner work, teacher spent 3/4 of time with one group prompting for on-task behavior or asking "what should you do now? What does factoring mean? What does expanding mean?"

k12_m_ca3_notes:
The lesson is grade-level appropriate and teacher provides several opportunities for students to work with grade-level material. Off-task behaviors, however, limit student engagement. 

Student discussion is focused on solution methods, though discussion protocols are not used to leverage student engagement. 

Teacher questioning is superficial and limited to getting students on-task or very high level. "What is expanding? What is factoring?" Teacher questioning funnels students towards an answer, rather than prompting student to deeply engage with the math. 

Conditions for engagement ARE present, though need refining to lead to better student outcomes (discussion/student work). Possible next step: provide MLRs and IRs for teacher to use in class, script and practice in coaching sessions.

k12_ela_standards:
Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development over the course of the text, including its relationship to supporting ideas; provide an objective summary of the text. (RI.8.2)

Engage effectively in a range of collaborative discussions (one-on-one, in groups, and teacher-led) with diverse partners on grade 8 topics, texts, and issues, building on others’ ideas and expressing their own clearly. (SL.8.1)
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: Students were given the last article written by Congressman John Lewis.  Students were directed to partner read the article with a peer within their small group and highlight important phrases and sentences that emphasize the gist of message being conveyed.  Students have a prescribed amount of time (12 minutes to review and discuss with their partners) while the teacher worked specifically with native Spanish speaking students.
k12_ela_ca2a: 3- Many questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 2- Few questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 3- Vocabulary questions and tasks mostly focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 3- Some questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: Teachers questioning and discussion prompts sought to build on students' learning; however, questions did not require students to cite or support their reasoning from the text when responding to questions. Example, teacher asks, 'what is the message he (author) is trying to convey?'  Student responds 'to stand up'.  Teacher  asks clarifying question of "stand up, how? By punching people or violence?"  Student replied 'no, by using your voice.'  Teacher also plays a media clip of the same article narrated to further engage students in the content and obtain a summary of the content through whole group discussion.

k12_ela_ca3_notes: Teacher employed partner groups to deepen and extend students' learning. Students were able to share their thoughts and ideas with their peers through their discussions but lack of accountable talking stems or questions for students to discuss in their partner groups limited their conversations. Teacher circulated between groups to ask questions such as 'what was his message to the world' and 'what is he asking you, as the next generation to do?"  Sudent responses included, 'stand up for what you believe in,' 'do the right thing, and 'know your history'.  However, teacher did not ask for nor did students cite or provide evidence from the text to support their responses.

fsot_ac1_notes: '-Teacher follows HMH foundational skills-aligned curriculum with fidelity, she also differentiated the lesson to meet the needs of 3 different grade levels of learners (12:1:1 bridge classroom)
fsot_td_notes:
'-Teacher correctly pronounced the sounds (T, not t/uh/ with a schwa) Teacher ensured that students also enunciated correct sound. 
-The lesson had a tactile, letter exploration box which students were excited about and also aligned to the lesson objective. 
-Teacher modeling of letter formation was strong think aloud that gave students exact way ("Start at the sky line, go down to the grass line. I lift my pencil and cross at the plane line")
fsot_sp_notes: '-Student participation was differentiated based on exactly what skill the students needed. Some students had slant boards with dry erase grips to form letters, some students had tactile box (non verbal learners) and others had standard writing paper. Students received academic feedback with multiple opportunities to say and form letters. (does your T look like mine? Let's make sure we start up here at the sky line. That will make our letter a lowercase t")
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher had checklist from Student Achievement Partners tool that allowed her to keep individual notes about student performance in relation to the objective. She kept checklist and data near as she conferenced with students to give academic feedback.

fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher direction instruction, student practice, assessment and differentiation
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows fundations scope and sequence for grade level 1 to provide today's lesson. Teacher delivers lesson of phonics and word awareness through activities such as "drill sounds","trick words", and "word play".
fsot_td_notes: Teacher noted "s" for bugs when it should have been the "z" sound. Teacher corrected after asking coach. Text was not used nor required in this particular lesson. Teacher provides opportunities for practice throguh speaking, listening, and writing in student notebooks. Teacher employs engagement strategies in a child friendly manner.
fsot_sp_notes: Teacher asks students to repeat words chorally, make words, tap words, and write sentences in student notebooks. Teacher employs oral tasks via drill sounds and tapping as well as sentences in student notebooks however puzzles, games, were not used. Upon my departure centers were beginning.
fsot_ad_notes: Data collection was doen informally and coach corrected student work. There were no samples collected. Centers were beginning at my departure which is differentiated during this block but I cannot say I observed but evidence that they will be used was shown.

fsot_1: Fundations, Unit 2 Level K-- blending cvc words
fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher direction instruction, student practice and assessment and differentiation.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows scope and sequence of Fundations manual to teach blending of cvc words via "tapping".
fsot_td_notes: Teacher ensures accurate pronunciation of sounds and provides visual aids via modeling. Objective was not explicitly stated. Text were not used nor required in this K lesson. Students have opportunities to practice orally via "drill sounds" and blending as well as practice writing in their notebooks. Students echo "a-apple-ah" and other words in song form but additional high energy activities were not employed.
fsot_sp_notes: Students practice blending a variety of cvc words with the help of teacher modeling such as set, met, rug, sun, log, let etc. Text was not used nor required in this particular K lesson. Students employ movement with sky writing and written tasks in their notebooks but other modalities were not employed.
fsot_ad_notes: Informal data was collected of students echoing sounds correctly and repeating chorally. There was no use of formal data collection. On the spot corrections were given for sound and spelling. There was no evidence of planned supports.

fsot_ad_notes: Sampling of dictation responses was employed but there was no other formal data techniques employed. fsot_targeted_skills:
SWBAT identify the letters qu, z
SWBAT identify and find all known constants and vowels, including qu, z by using their magnetic tile boards.
fsot_ac1_notes:
'-Teacher following the lesson script of Fundations will fidelity
-Teacher demonstrated evidence of following scope and sequence of curriculum ("remember yesterday when we practiced our vowel sounds. Our mouth is open as we extend the sounds here..")
fsot_td_notes:
'-Pacing allowed for students to be able to have direct instruction and independent practice. Students were on the carpet for 14 minutes, then transitioned back to their tables for 10 minutes of independent echo find with their magnetic tiles
-4-5 students were whispered or off task during the lesson
-Teacher directed letter formation of /qu/ and /z/ was not clear for students. Although teacher model was clear ("qu is a plane line letter, it starts at the plane line")  the materials were unorganized and students were not tuned in and listening, rendering the model ineffective.
fsot_sp_notes:
'-Although the student practice materials were aligned and clear, students struggled to access the materials. Magnet boards were all in a pile, students spent 2-3 minutes trying to find their personal magnet board and teacher had to individually help several students in the process. 
-Teacher circulated to give feedback to kids once the Echo letter find portion began. Feedback was accurate and helpful ("find the letter that says /qu/. Does /k/ say /kw/? Look at my mouth now")
fsot_ad_notes:
'-Little evidence of assessment and differentiation beyond the academic feedback provided during the student work portion. 
-Teacher did not pull any group, and there was no evidence of teacher writing notes informally to keep track of what students were demonstrating during student work portion. 
-Teacher appeared unaware that many students had missed the letter writing model, and continued the lesson without engaging in an informal check for understanding.

fsot_targeted_skills: Focus on identifying and sounding out glued sounds in words, along with digraphs and practicing Trick Words/Sight Words.
fsot_ac1_notes: Stella is aligned to the scope and sequence and is on pace with the grade level curriculum.
fsot_td_notes: Stella has improved her model and is very clear, doesn't add any superfluous talk. It aligns to the technical phonemic language and holds the bar for kids with the same language.
fsot_sp_notes: Students were engaged and held accountable to the work. At all times, most of the students  were doing  the work and when a 1-2 students were not, both teachers held students  accountable.
fsot_ad_notes: The focus is for Stella & Arokium to now analyze the data from their assessment today and adjust their instruction immediately.

When reviewing the QW, a student tells the teacher that the COP is 7, the teacher asks, “How do you know it is seven?”
Problem of the Day: Rodrick goes to the supermarket to buy some onions for soup. Last week he bought 40 lbs of onions for $200. This week he paid… Did Rodrick pay the same amount per pound of onions this week, as last week?
The teacher prompts students to identify their noticings and wonderings, circulating the room while they work independently. 
The teacher sets up an opportunity for students to turn and talk: “Before I review the answer, I want you to turn to your partner behind you and discuss what you wrote.” The students are engaging with one another and the teacher continues to prompt students, asking them “what do you notice?” 
The teacher was prepared with ladder questions that prompted students to explain their thinking, “How can we use what we know about how much he spent last week to help us?”
“How can we compare the amount of money he spent last week to the amount of money we spent this week?”

fsot_targeted_skills:
Target 1: Identifying vowel sounds and syllables in words.
Target 2: Have students add/remove sound endings to words.
fsot_ac1_notes:
Teacher says different words to students. Students listen to the word and observe the teacher's lips to identify the words being heard correctly. 

Words like /por/ch/, /spar/k/, /per/ch/, /por/ch/: Teacher broke the beginning word sounds and spoke which sounds should be included at the end of the sounds. Students were systematically called to answer and successfully able to add the ending to the word sounds.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher provides adequate time for students to engage with the speaking and listening task. All students are actively engaged and eager to hear their "numbers" called so that they could participate. Students successfully demonstrated
fsot_sp_notes: Although students were engaged and eager to learn, they were not given multiple opportunities to practice the targeted skills. Additionally, only students that were called on were being given the opportunity to participate, therefore all voices were not heard and there was no clear indication as to how data is being gathered to see which students have mastered the lesson and which ones did not.
fsot_ad_notes: No observation of differentiation was indicated.

Teacher has colorful charts of word blends with corresponding pictures for students as she points to each pair/team and then waits for students to repeat the sounds.

Additionally, the teacher calls students individually to orally share words. Teacher has a checklist of all student names and checks off which student being called so every student has a chance to participate. However, time does not allot for all students to participate without having to move on in the lesson.
fsot_ad_notes:

fsot_1: Identify,deleting and adding phonemes and where to we take away the sounds
fsot_targeted_skills: Identify,deleting and adding phonemes and where to we take away the sounds
fsot_ac1_notes:
Teacher says the words: /crawl/, /torn/, /laws/, /cause/. The expectation is that all students repeat the words in unison. Students repeat the sounds and some use the “roller coaster” method to help them close the word.

Teacher says: "We segment words into sounds we hear /law/and say how many sounds they hear, 2, /card/,3, /thaw/2, /storm/4, /caught/,3, /burst/,
T: We are adding final phonemes, /fir/ add /m/, /yol/ add /k/, /straigh/ /t/, /doo/ add /m/, /cor/ add /d/, /shoo/ add /t/. 
Now let’s delete phonemes and where to we take away the sounds from. /craw/ without /l/, /fault/ without /t/, sauce without /ce/, /stern/ without /n/, /chalk/ without /k/
Time to substitute final phonemes. I will change the ending sound and you say the word. /wide/ change /d/ to /s/ (wise), /pork/ change /k/ to /ch/, /mark/ change /k/ to ch/ (march)"

Teacher shows 3 dots on a dry erase board and breaks each word up into syllables (sounds). Teacher says the words and student share out where each letter (sound) should be placed.
W - i- de
W - i - se
W - i - pe
W - i - fe
fsot_td_notes: Teacher is upbeat, and uses a strong voice to call out words. Teacher is intentional in making sure the words are said loud and clear for students to hear and repeat accurately.
fsot_sp_notes: Students are seated on the rug and  all share out words and sounds (phonemes) in unison. Not all students actively participate and others began getting off task. Reading groups should be created to meet all students where they are (high leveled readers can read independently during the phoneme instruction since the material is redundant to them) lower level could stay on the rug to continue receiving targeted instruction.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher actively scans the room while students repeat words and holds students accountable that repeat words incorrectly. Teacher will repeat word sounds and then have the individual students and whole class repeat together.

fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, and assessment and differentiation.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows the specific scope and sequence for grade level K to provide today's lesson. Teacher delivers a story time lesson as designed: introducing students to awareness for print visualization, understanding story structure, comprehension and verbal memory.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher reviews the cover of the book and asks students what an author does, what an illustrator is, highlights the pictures, and the purpose for today's lesson as designed. As teacher reads with enthusiasm there are pauses taken throughout the story to ask students to identify the letter and specific sound such "g, game, guh" as well as "k, kite, k" in the story. Teacher also employs students to identify if it is a capital letter or lower case letter and where else they see this letter around the room. Teacher asks students “What kind of e is this E?” What words start with E?” to push their awareness of words in the text as well. Students echo teacher in sing-song manner as they read their ABCs.
fsot_sp_notes: Students practice orally of ABCs through echoing of the teacher during story time and then are transitioned to their letter boards for a matching activity of the alphabet in the correct order in table groups. Teacher loses some time with pacing at the end of the by focusing on ensuring letters are right side up. All students although at different speeds accurately matched the correct letter to the correct box and in the correct order.
fsot_ad_notes: Informal data was collected during drill sounds by teacher. This is evidenced for  when teacher says "K kite kuh" teacher then says "ooh I want to hear that sound again" as well "remember its not up up - its you up uh". Teacher also uses formal assessment data to have supporting teacher pull a small group to review specific drill sound letters students need additional practice with in the back of the classroom. Teacher circulates throughout all tables to support with alphabetization as needed.

fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, assessment and differentiation.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows scope and sequence for grade level K to provide today's lesson. Teacher delivers lesson on blending and tapping out and blending CVC words as well as sky writing capital letters I and J.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher provides clear instruction of lesson and provides students with opportunities to engage through listening and speaking but not through reading (as this was not required for today's lesson). Lesson is presented in a child friendly manner through the use of the smart board, pre-planned power point with required materials, and "mama echo" to reward and engage students in their learning.
fsot_sp_notes: Students are given the opportunity to practice identifying their letters and sounds through drill sounds and to practice their formation of capital letters I and J through their student notebooks. Teacher provides verbalization for students to sky write then trace these letters as designed and then students have the opportunity to practice forming these letters independently in their student notebooks. Most students are engaged in the lesson but 2/8 need re-direction to trace letters and to correctly tap out letters 1 by 1 on fingers.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects informal data through drill sounds and has students repeat sounds that are not said correctly and scans for 100% to ensure all students repeat if not all have done so. There was no evidence of formal data collection.

fsot_1: Fundations/ Unit 3/ Blending and building cvc words
fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, assessment and differentiation.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows grade level K fundations scope and sequence to deliver today's lesson. Teacher delivers lesson as designed by following the manual to teacher students to find letter using their letter boards and build cvc words using their letter boards.
fsot_td_notes: Teachers instruction is correct but not always explicit and clear as it relates to directions. Students are given too much time to find particular letters which sometimes to led to off task behavior/disruption. The use of the letter boards lends to itself to a lesson that is child friendly but students are not asked to apply learning via decodable text (not required in today's lesson).
fsot_sp_notes: Students all have the correct materials (letters and letter boards) to participate in today's echo find letters and echo find words activity. Students are asked to find letters, echo the sound, and begin to build two cvc words. Although most students were actively participating in the lesson I was only able to see 13/20 students properly building the cvc words correctly (fit and map) on their first go.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects formal data by circulating to tables and individual students and asking them what says? by inserting a particular sound. Teacher corrects students who say a when the answer should be I as they confuse this sound. Evidence of adjusting instruction to support students was not demonstrated and there were opportunities to do as some students confused a, i, and e.

rater_role: Collaboratively between TL Staff/Coach and School/District Coaches/Leaders
fsot_targeted_skills: Asking and answering questions (introduced vocabulary as well).
fsot_ac1_notes: The G2 content was on pace with the Into Reading Module 5.
fsot_td_notes: The teacher failed to provide explicit instruction for the comprehension skill (asking and answering questions). She gave a quick kid-friendly definition of the vocabulary.
fsot_sp_notes: While kids were compliant, there was little to no engagement for active participation.
fsot_ad_notes: Not observed at all and no data collection tool or questions around students' answers.

rater_role: Collaboratively between TL Staff/Coach and School/District Coaches/Leaders
fsot_targeted_skills: Blending CVC words and letter sound/ID practice.
fsot_td_notes:
Teacher had provided strong model; however, there were few instances where the teacher made errors: /kuh/, /l/ and /wuh/. She did model soundly for segmenting/blending. 

She gave students choice for how to blend CVC and she had a vowel cheer.

Her pacing mirrored the expectation for Drill Sound/Warm-Up and gave students accurate time practicing. 

Multiple opportunities for practice out of context: skywrite, letter sound cards, vowel extension, CVC blending along with using the word in a sentence.
fsot_sp_notes: While students were looking and compliant, there were several who were not practicing without the full accountability. Teacher was looking and asked to repeat, but there were a number of moments where they were not held to practice or how to address it.
fsot_ad_notes: Miller has a collection tool and updates it consistently; however, in today's lesson she didn't respond to some of the mistakes effectively (/i/ sound was mistaken for /e/ sound).

fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, assessment and differentiation
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows scope and sequence to deliver grade 2 Fundations lesson for today's unit. Teacher delivers lesson on vowel teams as well as fluency and comprehension through "Story time".
fsot_td_notes: Teacher provides opportunity for drill sound leaders to demonstrate their knowledge of vowel teams, standard sound cards, and suffixes in the front of the class which is done in an engaging and child friendly manner while students echo. Students also are provided appropriate time and have text in front of them to practice fluency while reading independently and demonstrate comprehension in a decodable text "Wish Come True" as designed.
fsot_sp_notes: Students actively participate in the content of the lesson through reading independently, reading out loud to class, and underlining evidence from the text. Students are also asked to justify their reasoning for whether or not Beth (the main character) would make a good pet owner based on the text.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects informal data during drill sounds as evidenced when she said "Stop right there “e-d, ed” and had students repeat this suffix sound. The teacher also notices during the story time share out that students are not properly answering the question "What did Beth do?" and are providing answers on what the mom did. The teacher had students refine their answers by reviewing the text again but did not necessarily change their instruction. Teacher also did not circulate as students were marking text to see what students were identifying as a means of collecting formal data.

fsot_1: Fundations/Unit 3 re-teach/ ay, a-e, and ai vowel teams
fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, and assessment/differentiation
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows scope and sequence to provide additional lessons on the vowel teams -ai, ay, and a-e as designed for grade level 2 Fundations.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher models blending the words pay the standard sound cards and explains how the ending of -ay sounds different the middle sound of -ai. Teacher asks for a variety of volunteers to then practice giving words with -ay and -ai using poster board and asks a variety of CFUs so students can justify how they know it is the appropriate sound. Students do not engage in decodable text.
fsot_sp_notes: Teacher delivers mini lesson then instructs students to return back to their seat to complete a worksheet at their tables of utilizing the proper -ay, -ai, or a-e vowel teams as they've just learned.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects informal data as evidenced by "Why do you think ai? "So Tray, is that gonna have -ai in the middle or -ay the end?" and the lesson is prepared because of formal assessment data. In the moment adjustments were not noted being made.
