fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, assessment & differentiation
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows scope and sequence for Pre-K part 1. Teacher delivers capital letter S lesson as designed.
fsot_td_notes: The teacher delivers lesson in a child friendly manner for Pre-K via "baby echo", movement, songs, and chants to learn letter/sound awareness of A-Z with today's focus being on letter S.
fsot_sp_notes: Most students engage in oral tasks that are aligned to the targeted content via "drill sounds" (3/14 do not) but do not have opportunities to work out of context via puzzles or games. The lesson is primarily designed for teacher direct instruction and modeling of how to write letter S at this stage. Teacher brings outside opportunities via lining up students by letter and the Fundations randomization of letters card desk for additional practice.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects informal data via questioning as evidenced by "does anybody know what sound the letter S make? "remember one of our friends starts with a S", "what else makes the sound "sss"?". Formal data collection was not demonstrated in this lesson.

fsot_targeted_skills: SWBAT use what they know about letters and sounds to write a draft narrative
fsot_ac1_notes:
'-Writing lesson and unit was written internally as an extension to the ELA curriculum
-writing objectives based on topic of study and phonics skills as taught in Fundations
fsot_td_notes:
'-Teacher directed questioning was strong and put thinking lift on students (What were some..? How do you know..? Why do you think...?)
-Teacher model and think aloud was clear and accurate. Included active think aloud on how to write and identify first and final sounds, finger spacing. Students were able to see encoding in action through the model
fsot_sp_notes:
'-students had enough time to actively work on their drafts, including sketching, labeling, and writing
-Students were asked to discuss their ideas with a table, allowing them processing time
-Student practice materials were aligned with Fundations unit (Fundations writing paper was used)
fsot_ad_notes:
'-Writing paper was differentiated with sentence stems and word lists for lower level students, however students weren't able to access the content with this differentiation and it caused additional confusion (ie student had snowman copied on their paper, but didn't know what it said) 
-Differentiation of materials did not match student development writing stages
-Student groups were differentiated by the topic they chose, not the skill of their writing which was a missed opportunity for teacher to support small group and gather data on orthography.

fsot_1: Fundations/ Unit 2/ Story Time & Echo Find Letters
fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, assessment & differentiation.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher delivers K fundations lesson following scope and sequence in manual. Lesson delivery included a story time lesson on identifying the ABCs as well as participating in echo find letters of a dictated sound.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher often delivers clear and accurate instruction and needs minor adjustments from coach as it relates to teaching as designed. K lesson did not require use of decodable text as students are not yet at that stage so they were listening to a read aloud. All materials and activities presented by teacher were kid friendly and done with high energy using sing song techniques and chants.
fsot_sp_notes: All students have opportunities to practice identifying their ABCs and placing them in chronological order via the letter board manipulatives/puzzles. Students also participate orally via read aloud and drill sounds. 100% of students build ABCs via on letter boards accurately and 98% students find their letters/sounds for echo find letters accurately (minus 1 or 2 who are new to the language/class).
fsot_ad_notes:
Teacher collects informal data via dictation responses and holds students accountable for proper echoing correct sounds this was evidence when said "-Do that one again Leangely" and when
"Elias says p - teacher says flip it" and he then says q-u. Teacher collects formal data with checklist towards the end of lesson when students were participating in echo find letters. Teacher did not adjust instruction based on observations of student work/practice and there was no evidence of differentiation.

fsot_1: Fundations/ Unit 3/ Tapping & Blending of CVC words
fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, and assessment & differentiation.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows aligned scope and sequence for today's lesson via Fundations grade K manual. Students used previously learned skill of tapping to blend cvc words to now learn the new concept to tap and blend words independently to read cvc words.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher holds students accountable for clear and accurate pronunciation during drill sounds. This was evidence when teacher said "look at my mouth and say aaaa". No text was required for this K lesson and opportunities were taken for students to practice writing their capital letters when given a dictated sound as well as writing the first letter of their name as a make it fun task.
fsot_sp_notes: Students practice writing their capital letters T and their name on their white boards as teacher dictates sound after teacher models. Differentiated support was provided via small group. Students however did not use puzzles as intended in the lesson via letter boards.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects formal data via checklist and differentiates via small group with multilingual learners at the front of the room. These students have been identified as those who need extra support from ongoing informal and formal assessment data.

fsot_1: Fundations/ Unit 7/ Introduction to glued sounds -ang, -ong, -ing, -ung
fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice, assessment and differentiation.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows Fundations 1 manual to deliver instruction following intended scope and sequence where students practice their new glued sounds via dictation spelling.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher models content specific task through drill sounds and holds students accountable for accurate pronunciation of sounds as well as during dictation spelling. Text dependent questions/text were not part of today's lesson. Pacing is spent primarily on one activity when the goal was four. Lesson is often presented in child friendly manner but does not lend itself to discussion or collaboration among students in table groups.
fsot_sp_notes: Students practice spelling via teacher dictation on their dry erase white boards. Students work with oral / written tasks but not puzzles and games. All students actively and correctly spell sounds -ong, -ing, -ang, -ung and the words with their new glued sounds sing and hung.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher notices when students did not box glued sounds while circulating and adjusted instruction by holding of a students white board with the correct work product and re-explaining to students the expectation. Teacher also adjusts instruction when noticing students confusing the spelling of long and lung. Teacher seats all students who need additional support at a differentiated table group to support them closely. Formal data was not collected.

fsot_targeted_skills: Aligned content, teacher directed instruction, student practice
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher follows fundations 1 grade level manual to deliver lesson on new glued sounds -am and -an. Teacher delivers lesson on how to tap out these words and blend them to form words with these endings.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher gives adequate practice time orally via drill sounds and student leaders are chosen to lead trick words, and vowel extension in child friendly manner and to fidelity. Appropriate pacing is provided sometimes as students did not get to practice with building -an words or marking their glued sounds in their student notebooks. Students were instructed to go right into practice of spelling words which comes after these activities.
fsot_sp_notes: Students practice with tapping out glued sounds after coach instructs to hold index finger to thumb for the first letter and bringing the middle finger and ring finger to the thumb for their glued sounds. Teacher then transitions students to letter boards so they can practice identifying their glued sounds after dictation and coach instructs them begin building a word with -am -- bam. Teacher then reviews -an glued sound and has students identify and build the word can.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects informal data during drill sounds as evidenced when they said "One more time, pause its “eh not itch”, "Echo after again Jayceon", "You’re just saying the sound not the word itch twice" to ensure accurate pronunciation. Teacher also says during vowel extension "future drill leader see how he traces it again as you’re making the sound do that next time". Teacher also asks a number of checks for understanding questions that include "what sound does this make again? How many letters does it have? When you’re tapping -am are you gonna tap it out individually or together?". Formal data was not collected during this lesson and some students adjusted their forming of the words after teacher circulated.

k12_ela_ca1_notes:
Teacher started the lesson with a review of adjectives by reading a poem titled, "Wandering through the Zoo" Teacher read a line such as, The birds colors are.... students were grouped in pairs then asked to refer to the adjective chart and complete the sentence.  
S: The bird colors are gorgeous.
T What word is an adjective?
S: gorgeous 

T: Read page 10 of "Just Ducks" and instructed students they will research how the mallard duck eats.  The book was displayed on the SmartBoard for students to read along. 
T: "‘Dabbling’ is when ducks nibble at the surface of the water with their beaks to get tiny bits of food—small insects and seeds."

Using a total participation technique, invite responses from the group:

T: "What does a duck do when it is dabbling?" 

T: Directed students attention to the posted learning target and read it aloud:

"I can find information and answer questions about a new kind of bird in the text Birds (Scholastic Discover More)."

T: Displayed Birds (Scholastic Discover More) read pages 20–21 aloud fluently and with expression, including the labels and captions.

Students went into buddy groups for independent work.

fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher is using grade level sound combinations and sight words for oral drill. Students chorally engage in phonics oral with direct feedback. Teacher uses Wonders lesson plan in context of 1st grade scope and sequence.
fsot_td_notes: Sound combination /wh/ pronounced incorrectly. Incomplete/confusing model of the a_e pattern with missing checks for understanding. Students practiced oral drill chorally with feedback from the teacher. Students used movements with sound combinations to remember sounds.
fsot_sp_notes: No opportunities within observation to practice identifying sight words or decoding text with sound combinations. Most students participating in choral oral drill with some support/feedback from teacher on pronunciation.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher is going through oral drill without making note of which students struggle with specific sounds/words. Teacher is trying to notice which students have acquired specific sounds or words but does not have a formal system for recording.

fsot_ac1_notes: Grade level oral drill. Wonders lesson within 1st grade scope and sequence.
fsot_td_notes: All models are clear and accurate. Explanation of a_e rule present and clear. No opportunity to apply learning to text or writing. Students chorally respond to each combination and word, allowing for consistent student practice. Evidence of clear engagement.
fsot_sp_notes: All students required to participate and given immediate feedback if not. Students are not given opportunity to practice independently or interact peer to peer as all practice is a teacher model followed by choral repetition.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher has no specified system for gathering data and does not adjust instruction in the moment.

fsot_ac1_notes: Grade level phonics oral drill. 1st grade Wonders lesson in a determined scope and sequence.
fsot_td_notes: Clear and accurate models of sound combinations and sight words. Slow pacing, students off task, delayed feedback.
fsot_sp_notes: Students have low accountability and become easily distracted. Students are inconsistently held accountable to participation. Students are not giving the opportunity to work out of context as lesson is designed to be oral drill.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher does not have system for collecting feedback and only appears to gather data informally. Teacher does not adjust instruction in the moment

fsot_ac1_notes: K reading lesson provided by school scope and sequence.

fsot_sp_notes: Students are unable to follow along in the lesson as they are asked to recall 3 previously read texts. Students are confused about what they are being asked and share random/off-task thoughts and observations. Only students who raise their hands are required to participate. Students do not do any independent work.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher has no clear system of data collection and makes no adjustments to data in the moment. Teacher inconsistently identifies when students are confused and/or off-task.

Teacher: "when we look at 4x=12 - 4y, how can I make this one look like that?"
Student: "Multiply x by 4"

Student "Theyre the same"
Teacher asks how they know, and adds "I can move it" - using informal language without pushing them toward precise mathematical language.

fsot_targeted_skills: I can use text features such as labels to identify the features of a bird.
fsot_ac1_notes: Today's lesson reflected aligned content as evidenced by the lesson having one central learning target aligned to the standards. This lesson target was: I can use text features such as labels to identify the features of a bird.
fsot_td_notes: The workshop model and gradual release of the teacher directed i do then we do was evidenced by Ms. Cohen demonstrating what a diagram is, students assisting with identifying which one is or is not a diagram. The visuals projected as well as the pictures to the side supported students making meaning of labels vs. diagrams.
fsot_sp_notes: After the i do, we do, students are then released to the "you do" portion of the workshop model. This allowed students to apply the skill of finding and drawing a label based on their chosen text in pairs about bugs, chicken, or lady bugs etc.
fsot_ad_notes:
There was informal data collected during the we do process if students incorrectly identified the labels but no formal data was collected during groups. There were also students who were struggling and would've benefitted from differentiated work such as pre-filled in definitions as well as the book title to support SWDs/ells with writing as noted that the orange pairing struggled with reading and identifying what the labels were– their primary understanding was the image of the chicken.

In addition, the visuals/models present to support learners were there but continuing to project your slide 7 during partner time to support students in defining labels on their worksheet would’ve been great! When asked, many students were confusing labels with pictures.

fsot_targeted_skills: LT: I can record my observations with words and drawings like a researcher.
fsot_ac1_notes: Today's lesson reflected grade level standards and had one central learning target aligned to the standards as evidenced by :: LT: I can record my observations with words and drawings like a researcher.
fsot_td_notes: Workshop model of i do, you do, was evidenced by the teacher sharing key vocabulary with students as well as doing a close reading, a turn & talk opportunity was also provided.
fsot_sp_notes: After the teacher directed lesson students crafted their own sentences of what it means to be living/non-living at their tables to begin their preliminary research.
fsot_ad_notes: Your writing checklist provided an assessment criteria for students to follow as they crafted their sentences and scaffolded support was evidenced by the worksheet sentence stems as well as the research images to be able to circled. I suggest also ensuring you review the criteria prior as well to ensure students quickly hear it before going off. There was evidence of teacher circulating to table groups to provide support and correct students.

fsot_td_notes: Workshop model of i do, you do, we do was evidenced by you demonstrating what a diagram is, students assisting you in identifying which one is or is not a diagram, and then students finding and drawing the diagrams based on their text in pairs. Your visuals projected as well as the pictures to the side supported students making the meaning of labels vs. diagrams. More child friendly engagement could've been demonstrated via video and songs.
fsot_sp_notes: Students assisting you in identifying which one is or is not a diagram and then students finding and drawing the diagrams based on their text in pairs allowed for student practice. Students in smaller also had the opportunity to practice labeling an image of a bird as an additional scaffold after a close reading. There was a nice balance of struggle in the larger group as students had to find the diagram in their text with their pairs and positive work environment among students.
fsot_ad_notes: Differentiation / accommodations / scaffolds were present for ELLs/SWDs as evidenced by Ms. Galvin pulling 4 students for small group instruction and moving at a pace best suited for students. Students also had access to the text being read aloud during small group and the release model was differentiated to include providing students a picture of a bird to label as a scaffold while the other group had the least scaffolded.

9:29 T: You’re gonna need your math workbook today. Reviews agenda. 
OPen your workbook and find some space - that’s where you’re going to write your estimation. Here’s your first estimation. Projects an image of  a package with bows (gifts) and Ss have to estimate how many are in the package. Gives 30 seconds. 
9:32 Answer is 50 deluxe bows. Student with closes (51) gets a lolli
T: Do you want to explain how you came up with that number?
S: I knew it wasn’t going to be 100 so I divided by 2 and then thought it wound’t be 50 so I added 1.

9:34 Flip to our notes page. Project info about “Distributing”, with the goal of clearing hte parenthesis. Anytime we have a number next to a parentheses, which operation should you be thinking of?
S: Multiplication
T: Yes. So any time we have a situation where we have a parentheses, we have to clear it before we can solve. Once we’ve done that, then we can solve the problem. 

Ex: -4(x+3)=8

T: We can either distribute to terms inside the parenthesis or divide both sides fo the equation or inequality

T: What is the amount we need to distribute?
S: -4
T: What does it mean to distribute the -4 to the terms inside?
S: Is it when you add the 4.
T: Ok, when we see a number next to the parentheses, what operation?
S: Multiplication. 
T: Why can’t we combine x+3?...We don’t know the value of x. So let’s take the value outside and multiply by each term inside hte parentheses. SO we multiply by -4. So we have -4x…what else do I do. 
S: -4 x 3
T: So -4 x 3, what does that give us?
S: -12
T: Am I going to distribute this -4 to the 8 or am I done?
S: You’re done. 
T: Yeah, all we need to worry about is distributing the -4. Once it’s done, we dont have to worry about it anymore. Now we have a standard equation we can solve. The other way is to clear out the -4 by taking the whole left side of the equation and dividing by -4. What do you think that would leave us with?
S: x+3
T: Yeah…you’re just cancelling it out and all you’re left with is x+3. So would we just be left with x+3 = 8?
S: No…don’t we have to divide that side by -4?
T: Yeah, what we do on one side we have to do on the other side. So what does that give us…-2.

-5(z+3) = 7.4
T: So taking a look at our 1st one, any thoughts on how to get started? What do you think, Liz?
S: We have to look at the parenthesis part.
T: What do we wanna do with our parenthesis here? Can we combine z and 3 here? What can we do instead to get this into a workable equation?
S: Don’t we have to make the -5 into a 5?
T: Not quite. We don’t need to change this, but we need to do something.
S: Distribute it.
T: Yes, how?
S: You do -5 x z and then -5 x 3.
T: Writes on board to show -5z - 15 = 7.4 At this point, we’re just looking at a standard 2step equation. 
S: Why am I confused? Why don’t we remove the -5?
T: Do we want to look at the additional amount or our z?
S: Additional amount. 
T: So will I clear out the -15 here?
S: Add 15.
T: What else am I doing?
S: Add it to the 7.4
T: What else am I going to do here?
S: -15 +15 is 0. ….7.4+15, what? Uses calculator to get 22.4
T: We cleared out the 15. What is the other term we have left?
S: -5z. What do we have to do?
T: We’ll find out now. Now we have -5z=22.4. We need to know what 1z is equal to, so what do we do?
S: Divide by 5 on both sides
T: Writes on board to show z=4.48. If i wanted to check, how can I do that?
S: Plug in the -4.48 for z.

For the warm-up activity, the students had the opportunity to share their thinking about how they solved the problems mentally. Students were able to come up to the board to explain their thinking. 2.1 Activity (Which is longer? Which is shorter? We can compare each other. Both teachers stood next to each other to describe what is longer and who is shorter. One teacher stood on a chair and the teacher asked "Can we compare each other like this?" The students responded "No because we have to line it up tip to tip."

The students were provided with a bucket of materials (pencil, scissors, marker, crayon, a playing card, sentence strips with "shorter than" and "longer than", etc.). As students are working in their groups, the teacher walks up to each group and sets up their materials with the sentence strip to help guide students on thinking about which objects were shorter and longer. In addition, before the students were asked to work with their partners to measure objects in comparison to the pencil, the teacher compares the pencil to the wand and a pencil to the marker. Both of the examples made it seemed to be more guided practice.

As students are working in their groups to measure the objects in comparison to the pencil, the teacher visits each group to check for understanding. It does not appear that the teacher strategically shares students representations or solution methods. The teacher calls a student from each group to come up and compare their object to the pencil. The teacher says "We have to see if we agree or disagree with their thinking." The object that each student brings to the front of the classroom is added to the anchor chart whether it is shorter or longer than the pencil. The students are asked to say the comparison statement ("The straw is longer than the pencil"). 

The teacher summaries the warm-up activity by listing the different strategies the students used to solve the problems. The teacher summarized the comparison activity to the pencil by stating "We were comparing 2 objects to a 3rd object. We know when we measure length, we are measuring how long something is, how short something is." At the end of the lesson, the teacher summarizes the activity that asks students to measure the length and height of their desk. Teacher says "Let's review what we just did. What were we measuring? This side which is the length. We were measuring the height. What did you notice about the length and height of the desk?" Student responded "one is longer and one is shorter." The teacher explains the length of the desk is shorter and the height of the desk is longer."

k12_m_learning_goal: Let’s use some tools to measure angles.
k12_m_standards:
4.MD.C.5.a
An angle is measured with reference to a circle with its center at the common endpoint of the rays, by considering the fraction of the circular arc between the points where the two rays intersect the circle. An angle that turns through 1/360 of a circle is called a “one-degree angle,” and can be used to measure angles.

4.MD.C.5.b
An angle that turns through one-degree angles is said to have an angle measure of  degrees.

4.MD.C.6
Measure angles in whole-number degrees using a protractor. Sketch angles of specified measure.

4.MD.C.7
Recognize angle measure as additive. When an angle is decomposed into non-overlapping parts, the angle measure of the whole is the sum of the angle measures of the parts. Solve addition and subtraction problems to find unknown angles on a diagram in real world and mathematical problems, e.g., by using an equation with a symbol for the unknown angle measure.

4.NBT.B.5
Multiply a whole number of up to four digits by a one-digit whole number, and multiply two two-digit numbers, using strategies based on place value and the properties of operations. Illustrate and explain the calculation by using equations, rectangular arrays, and/or area models.

10:32 T: Passes out warm-up and says “Our warm-up today has four statements and you’re going to determine whether they’re true or false….You have about 1 minute to do the warm-up.
10:42 Starts lesson by projecting slide about a ray that turns all the way around to make a full 360 degree turn. 
T: We’re also going to talk about fractions today. Uses cards to make pairs for students to work. Goes around the room to have students pull a card from the deck to ID partner.
10:46 Done making pairs and brings kids to circle in front. 
T: We’re going to figure out what fraction of a full turn do these degrees represent. …So which form should our answers be in?
S: Degrees.
T: Nope.
S: Choral (fractions)
10:51 One group has finished the work, but rest of pairs don’t know how to get started. One group placed the given degrees as a numerator in a fraction, but didn’t know what to put as a denominator. One student for first degree given (120) added it 3 times to make 360. But she couldn’t make a fraction without T support, who worked with her starting at about 10:48.
10:53 Two more pairs have answers down, but none of the groups with answers have any work shown. 
10:55 T: Ok i’m going to give a couple more minutes because most groups haven’t gotten there.
10:59 Students who completed the assignment are helping other groups.
11 T: I know some of us have finished and some of us haven’t. I’m happy to see that those of you who finished early found something to do and went and helped others. That’s a big moment in this classroom.
11:02 Students continue completing the degrees/fraction activity.
6 Students finished are talking/playing towards the back of the class, away from kids still working. 3 Finished students still attempting to help their classmates. 
11:04 T: bring class back together. “I know some of us haven’t finished but most of us are on the right track…but we’re going to start working with our protractors.”
T: What you need to look at is, how is 1 degree shown on the protractor. And, how many of them do you see? Does that make sense?
1 S says yes. 
T: Ok, so how does it show and how many do you see (proceeds to pass them out)
11:07 8/20 students are using the protractor to try and answer the questions.
11:09 2 students have answered the 2 questions

The teacher mentioned to me that the students just completed the fraction unit before beginning this unit. k12_m_ca3_notes:
For the warm-up activity, the teacher asks, "What do you know about inches?" One student responds, "An inch is about this long." Another student responds, "ruler and measurement." A third student responds, "an inch is bigger than a centimeter." A fourth student responds, "There are 12 inches in a foot." 

There was limit use of precise mathematical language and how to use the ruler appropriately. For example, the students were asked to find 3 objects in the classroom and measure them with your partner. The teacher asked, "When you get your ruler, what does your ruler start with? What does your ruler end with?" A student responds, "0 and ends with 9." There is not discussion around the type of unit used with the ruler or how to appropriately use the ruler when measuring. 

The students were asked to partition each whole into half on their ruler. The teacher said, "When you finish, you should have a tick mark in between each whole. You and your partner will use that ruler, so you can get a more precise measurement. What happened when you measurement the second time? The student respond, "It was different." The teacher asked, "Why was it different?" The student responded, "Now that we partitioned the ruler into half - if it was 7 now, it is 7 1/2." There was very little of students explaining their thinking.  

When the students measured with the ruler around the classroom and then partitioned it into halves, students spent a considerable amount of time working on these problems, which may be evidence of perseverance. They did not seem to be productively struggling. 

Towards the end of the lesson, the teacher asks, "How could these 2 numbers show the same length (4 1/2 and 9/2)?" The teacher then asks, "What two things does this fraction have (4 1/2)?" A student responds, "A whole number and a fraction." The teacher asks one student to try and find 4/12 and 9/2. The teacher could have asked all of her students to find these fractions on the number line before sharing the answer out loud. The students could have had an opportunity to explain their thinking.

k12_m_learning_goal: Add numbers within 1,000 using place value strategies that include composing a ten.
k12_m_standards:
2.NBT.B.5
Fluently add and subtract within 100 using strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction.

2.NBT.B.7
Add and subtract within 1000, using concrete models or drawings and strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction; relate the strategy to a written method. Understand that in adding or subtracting three-digit numbers, one adds or subtracts hundreds and hundreds, tens and tens, ones and ones; and sometimes it is necessary to compose or decompose tens or hundreds.
k12_m_ca1a: Yes- The enacted lesson focuses only on mathematics within the grade-level/ course-level standards.
k12_m_ca1b: Yes- The enacted lesson builds on students’ prior skills and understandings.
k12_m_ca1c: Yes- The enacted lesson explicitly targets the aspect(s) of Rigor called for by the standard(s) being addressed.
k12_m_ca1_notes: From the warm-up activity to the lesson activity, I could observe the students had prior knowledge on combinations of ten. The teacher also provided the students with a anchor chart on composing a ten. The students seemed very familiar how to break apart a number to solve it.
k12_m_ca2a: 4- A variety of instructional techniques and examples are used to make the mathematics of the lesson clear.
k12_m_ca2b: 4- Student solution methods are shared, and connections to the mathematics are explicit and purposeful. If applicable, connections between the methods are examined.
k12_m_ca2c: 4- There are checks for understanding used throughout the lesson to assess progress of all students, and adjustments to instruction are made in response, as needed.
k12_m_ca2d: 3- The lesson includes a summary with a focus on the mathematics.
k12_m_ca2_notes:
During the warm-up activity, the students used multiple strategies to solve the problems (break-apart, counting up, composing a ten). Also, for the problem 67 + 23, a student replies, "90." He said he used the problem before (67 + 3 = 70) to help him solve this problem (67 + 3 = 70, 70 + 20 = 90). 

After completing the number talks, the teacher puts an anchor chart on the board of a completed problem that involves adding a 3 digit and 3 digit number. The teacher says, "Can you find what I did to solve the problem? Do the steps make sense? Can you explain it? Turn and talk to your partner." The students talk to their partner and then shared their thinking aloud. The teacher asked, "Did you notice I did not break apart the 250 into hundreds?" 

After discussing the problem on the anchor chart, the teacher asks, "What was the same in every problem we solved?" A student responds, "Each one has the strategy of making a ten or breaking apart." The teacher replies, "We might have to use different strategies based on the problem." This was an example of summarizing the learning before moving onto the lesson activity. 

While the students are working on the lesson activity of completing one set of addition problems, the teacher is walking around to check for misconceptions and understanding. For example, a student asked the teacher if she could use a number line to solve the problem, but wasn't how to do complete it. As the teacher is walking around the classroom, it appears he is strategically taking pictures of student work. He displays the student work on the board. He chose the same problems to show in a sequence; however, each problem used a different strategy that used a combination of 10. He showed problems that used the break-apart method, base ten blocks, and the number line.
k12_m_ca3a: 4- Teacher provides many opportunities, and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3b: 4- Teacher provides many opportunities, and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3c: 4- Teacher provides many opportunities, and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3d: 4- Teacher provides many opportunities, and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3e: 4- Teacher provides many opportunities, and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3_notes:
For the warm-up activity, the teacher asks, "Why do we love a ten?" The student responds, "It is easy to work with." The teacher then goes on to say, "Let's add 3 digit number by composing a ten. What does composing a ten mean? Turn and talk to your partner." 

The students then engage in a Number Talk. Throughout this activity, the teacher asks, "Who can explain their thinking? and Is there a different strategy anyone used?" For the first problem 28 + 2, one student responds, "I just knew that 28 + 2 = 30 by counting up." Another student responded, "I covered the 20. I looked at the 8 + 2 = 10. Then I added 20 + 10 = 30." The teacher replies, "You just composed a ten, which is what our lesson is about." The students are provided multiple problems throughout the number talks and are asked to put up their hand signals when they are ready to share a strategy. The teacher also asked the students for their answers for the problem 28 + 12. The students gave 42 and 32. The teacher than asks, "Who would like to defend your answer." 

The teacher often guides the students to use the correct mathematical language when they are explaining their strategy. For example, for the problem 67 + 3, the teacher asks, "Can you explain your thinking?" The students replies, "70. I covered up the 6." The teacher replies, "When you say covered up the 6, you mean you are breaking apart the number and covering up the tens place." The student replies, "I break apart 67 into 60 and 7, I added 3 + 7 = 10. Then, I added 60 + 10 = 70." 

For the lesson activity, the teacher assigns each group a set of problems. He asks that the students work independently first before working with their group. The teacher asks the students, "While you are solving each problem, think about what patterns you find? Can you use base ten blocks or a strategy we used before?"

k12_m_ca1_notes: In the lesson plan, it explains that the students have been practicing answering "how many" questions and comparison questions about shapes composed of pattern blocks. Most of the students seem to be familiar with most of the names of the shapes. They seemed to understand how to answer "how many" or comparison questions. The students seemed to have difficulty coming up with a question to ask about their shapes or another student's shape.
k12_m_ca2a: 4- A variety of instructional techniques and examples are used to make the mathematics of the lesson clear.
k12_m_ca2b: 3- Student solution methods are shared, and some mathematical connections are made between them.

k12_m_ca2_notes:
Throughout the lesson activity, the teacher asks most of the students questions about their shapes and what type of shapes they were using. After the students make their first shape for the lesson activity, the teacher said, "We are going to do a gallery walk." Before we start, we need to think what is a question I could ask my friend about their shape." After the students complete the gallery walk, the teacher asked, "Did anyone come up with a question to ask?" A student responds, "I wonder why some of the made a circle but they had some sides." Another student responds, "I noticed if you add a blue rhombus, it would make half a triangle." A third student responds, "It looks like a trapezoid but it is made up of different shapes." 

To help students understand how to ask questions, the teacher displays one of the shapes a student created. The teacher says, "What's a question we can ask about this shape?" The teacher then responds, "What shapes did you use to make your big trapezoid?" The teacher displays another student's shape. The teacher asks, "What questions can we ask about this shape?" A student responds, "There is more green than red." Another student responds, "Why are there more green than red?" The teacher helps this student by saying, "How many green triangles and red trapezoids are in your shape?" 

For the second part of this activity, the teacher said, "We are now going to make a new shape, but we can only use 2 shapes. You need to think about a question someone can ask about your shape." The teacher provides 2 examples: "I have 10 triangles and 2 trapezoids, how many shapes do I have in all?" A student responds, "12." The teacher asked, "How do you know?" The student responds, "10 and 2 more makes 12." The teacher provides another example: "Do I have more triangles or more trapezoids?" Another students replies, "Triangles." The teacher walks around, asking the students questions ("I see one shape, what is your plan for your second shape?" "What two shapes are you used? Do you remember the name of them?") 

The teacher asked a student, "What is a math story or question can we ask about your shape?" The student responds, "I want to tell how many in all." The teacher finds a misconception and adjusts the lesson. The teacher said, "That is a great start, but that is the end of our problem." The student replies, "I have 26 pieces." The teacher responds, "What is your question?" The students replies, "I have ____green triangles and 3 red trapezoids." The teacher replies, "I have ___green triangles and 3 red trapezoids, how many do I have in all?"

k12_m_ca3_notes:
For the warm-up activity, the students are provided with a shape that has 3 green triangles and 6 blue rhombuses. The students wrote down what they wonder about and what they noticed with the shape. The students also asked questions about the shape (Example: Why are there 6 rhombuses and 3 triangles? How many shapes are there in all?). The teacher asked, "Can we figure out the answer to these questions? How?" 

For the lesson activity, the teacher asks the students, "Put together pattern blocks to make a shape." The teacher walked around to help students and check for understanding. As the teacher walked around, she asked the students, "What shapes are you using to make your shape?" A student responds, "squares." Another student responds, "I am making a rectangle." A third student responds, "hexagon." The teacher walked over to another student and asked, "How many sides are there on your shape? What is another shape that has six sides?" The student replied, "Hexagon." The teacher continues to walk around to the groups of students, taking pictures of the shapes, as well as asking questions to the students ("What do you know about a circle?" "How many sides does your shape have?") 

The teacher continues to walk around to another students. The teacher asks, "What is your question?" The students replies, "I have 11 rhombuses and 2 red _____." The teacher assisted the student in remembering the name of the shape. The student responds, "How many do I have in all?" The teacher displays this shape on the screen and repeats the questions for all students to hear. The teacher then adds, "How can Ms. Reynolds figure out how many in all?" A student responds, "Count them." Another student responds, "Use counters." A third student responds, "Look at them and count in my head." The teacher replies, "Can I use an equation?" Another student responds, "11 + 2 = 13." The teacher adds, "She told me there is 11 rhombuses and then I can count on."

k12_m_standards:
K.MD.A.1
Describe measurable attributes of objects, such as length or weight. Describe several measurable attributes of a single object.

K.MD.A.2
Directly compare two objects with a measurable attribute in common, to see which object has “more of”/“less of” the attribute, and describe the difference. For example, directly compare the heights of two children and describe one child as taller/shorter.

k12_m_learning_goal:
Let's think about decomposing before we subtract.

20 students
k12_m_standards:
2.NBT.A.1
Understand that the three digits of a three-digit number represent amounts of hundreds, tens, and ones; e.g., 706 equals 7 hundreds, 0 tens, and 6 ones. Understand the following as special cases:

2.NBT.B.7
Add and subtract within 1000, using concrete models or drawings and strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction; relate the strategy to a written method. Understand that in adding or subtracting three-digit numbers, one adds or subtracts hundreds and hundreds, tens and tens, ones and ones; and sometimes it is necessary to compose or decompose tens or hundreds.

2.NBT.B.9
Explain why addition and subtraction strategies work, using place value and the properties of operations.Explanations may be supported by drawings or objects.

We’ve been talking about subtraction and asking ourselves question? What was that question?
About ½ S raise handput hands in air.

T: Alright friends, who is ready to share their thoughts? Almost all Ss raise their hands.

T: How does it make it different from A?
S: It doesn’t have any tens. T writes that on board.
S2: I think it’s B because there are only tens and ones.
T: WRites on B to reflect S response.
S3: I think it’s C because it has 25 ones but it’s supposed to have 100 ones because that’s a hundred block. 
T: Oh, i see. ARe you thinking of decomposing?
S: yes.
T: Ok, so if they were trying to decompose this hundred block, there’d be more ones there.
S4: Maybe D because there are no ones. T writes on board.
S5: I think it’s D because it’s the only one that doesn’t equal 125.
T: Let’s see, didn’t even think about that one. A?
S: A few say yes.
T: This one (points to B)
S; A few say yes.
T: Points to C
S: A few say yes.
T: Does anyone think A doesn’t belong?
S6: Yes, it’s the only one that is just fine.
T: You mean that it has what?
S6: It has hundfreds, tens, ones.
T: So I think we all pointed out some really great things. If you can support why it doesn’t belong and it makes sense, that’s what we want. Summarizes the different approaches students took.

k12_m_learning_goal: Compare two fractions with the same denominator by reasoning about their size.
k12_m_standards:
3.NF.A.3
Explain equivalence of fractions in special cases, and compare fractions by reasoning about their size.

3.NF.A.3.d
Compare two fractions with the same numerator or the same denominator by reasoning about their size. Recognize that comparisons are valid only when the two fractions refer to the same whole. Record the results of comparisons with the symbols , =, or , and justify the conclusions, e.g., by using a visual fraction model.
k12_m_ca1a: Yes- The enacted lesson focuses only on mathematics within the grade-level/ course-level standards.
k12_m_ca1b: Yes- The enacted lesson builds on students’ prior skills and understandings.
k12_m_ca1c: Yes- The enacted lesson explicitly targets the aspect(s) of Rigor called for by the standard(s) being addressed.
k12_m_ca1_notes: In the first lesson activity, the teacher notes how some students were using their prior knowledge to show how something is greater than (I believe this referenced the use of the greater than, less than, equal to symbols). Also, I also the fraction vocabulary on the board and some were utilized throughout the lesson (numerator, denominator, unit fraction, and equivalent fractions).
k12_m_ca2a: 4- A variety of instructional techniques and examples are used to make the mathematics of the lesson clear.
k12_m_ca2b: 3- Student solution methods are shared, and some mathematical connections are made between them.
k12_m_ca2c: 4- There are checks for understanding used throughout the lesson to assess progress of all students, and adjustments to instruction are made in response, as needed.
k12_m_ca2d: 1- The lesson includes no summary of the mathematics.
k12_m_ca2_notes:
To begin the lesson activity, the teacher begins by saying, "Take a few minutes to decide which fraction is greater for each pair of fractions. I want you to use a tool that has been working for you (1/2 and 3/2)." The teacher begins to walk around to the students working. The teacher says, "I see some people are using the fraction strips. If you solve it, push yourself to the next level - how do you know?" The teacher continues to add, "I see some of you are using prior knowledge to show how something is greater than. It fascinates me how people find different ways to solve it. Let's take 2 minutes to walk around to see how other people have solved it." 

The teacher stops to help a student, "I noticed how you messed up with the numerator and denominator. Can I tell you the mistake I made?" The teacher draws the mistake on the board for everyone to see (She draws two halves and 3 thirds underneath it). The teacher asks, "What did I do wrong?" A student replies, "You are comparing 2 and 2 with denominators." The teacher adds on to the student's response by saying, "We are comparing how many halves there are." 

The teacher adds, "I noticed some people put a symbol in between." A student responds, "1/2 < 3/2. 1/2 is not greater than 3/2." The teacher replies, "1/2 is less than 3/2." 

When the students completed comparing the fractions, the students walked around to see how other students solved the problem. However, there were discussions around the different ways the students solved them. 

At the end of the lesson, the students are asked to compare multiple fractions. The teacher asks, "Use the symbol < or > to make each statement true. Who can come show me what symbol would go in between." A student comes to the board and writes 1/6 < 4/6 and then says "1/6 is less than 4/6." For the next problem, the student who was asked to complete it was struggling (4/4 ___ 5/4). The teacher provides some support, "Remember what Student A said about the denominator." The student did not understand this problem at first (I'm not sure if he understands it yet). The teacher could have used the fraction strips or drew both fractions to help prove the answer. 

The teacher ends the lesson by having the students play a game where they are asked to put two fractions on a number line and compare them. As I walked around to observe students playing, it seems the students understood how to use the number line and where the place the fraction on the number line.

k12_m_ca3d: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3e: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3_notes:
For the warm-up activity, the students are provided with two shaped fraction strips - one has a cloud on top of it, so you can see how many parts are shaded. The teacher asks the students, "What do you notice? What do you wonder? Turn and talk to your partner." A student responds, "I noticed that on the bottom one, 3 out of 4 are shaded." Another student responds, "I wonder why there is a big cloud." A third student responds, "I noticed that the top strip is partly blocked." A fourth student responds, "I noticed the cloud is at kind of the middle part." 

The teacher asks the students questions about the fraction strips, such as "How many parts can be shaded on the top strip?" "How many are there already?" "We think it could be 2/4 or 1/2. Talk to your table, what else could it be?" The teacher walks around to the groups of students. The teacher replies, "I heard it could be 2/4, 3/4, and 4/4. What is it not? How do you know?" 

For the second problem in the lesson activity, the students are asked to compare 3/8 and 2/8. The teacher says, "You can use the same strategy or push yourself to put it into words." The teacher asks, "Which one is bigger? How do you know?" Some students explained their thinking to their partner. The teacher then asks, "Did anyone have similar thinking to you? How?" A student responds, "She made the greater symbol." Another student responds, "I think 3/8 is bigger than 2/8 because the bottom is the same. 3 is bigger than 2." The teacher responds, "When the denominator is the same, we only have to compare the numerator."

fsot_1: Skyline ELA Unit 2 - Phonics practice through small group instruction
fsot_targeted_skills: R.F. 3- Phonics and Word Recognition- Know and apply grade level phonics and word analysis in decoding words
fsot_ac1_notes: Students were working in small groups/workstations on a variety of foundational skills including diagraphs, syllables, sight words, and  compound words.  A group also worked on the skill of identifying 'fact and opinion'. Students worked in small groups to build upon their phonetic skills with pre-determined activities and aligned worksheets based on the skill they were tasked with practicing. The teacher pulled a small group to focus on compound words using a card game.
fsot_td_notes: Students were engaged in various phonetic tasks based on their assigned groups.  Students were actively engaged and working with their peers.  The tasks were cognitively engaging and required active student participation within their groups.  Once the game portion of the activity was completed, students completed an aligned worksheet for the focus practice skill (diagraphs, syllables, sight words, etc.).
fsot_sp_notes: Students were actively engaged in the games and completed the assigned written tasks.  However, students completed worksheets that included multiple choice options and did not allow for more authentic student work deliverables.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher worked with her small group while a support person rotated between the other small groups to ensure students were on task.  No data was taken on students in real time.  However, teacher did collect their worksheets at the end of small groups and indicated she would use the formative data to inform her future instruction.

B. The teacher began the *all* activities by filling out the first 2 boxes taking away a cognitive lift from students and a potential productive struggle. There was struggle observed within the classroom however, it was not productive and students who were confused knew they would go over the problem and waited until that moment.

The teacher asks, "Why might you need to represent 354 in different ways." A student responds, "to show different strategies." 

To begin the lesson activity, the teacher provides the students with the problem 354 - 7. The teacher says, "You can use whatever strategy works best for you." The teacher starts to walk around to the students working. She asks the students, "What is your strategy you are using?" "Do you want to use break apart? Looks like you are doing this." "Do you have enough? What can you do?" 

After the students have some time to answer 354 - 7, the teacher asks, "Who can come up and show us a strategy they used to solve this problem." The teacher does not seem to strategically choose a student to share their thinking. A student comes to the board and draws the base ten blocks for 354. The student says, "I minus the 4 ones then I took away the 10." The teacher adds, "So you had a to decompose the ten into 10 ones?" The student marks off the base ten blocks to solve the problem. The teacher asked, "Did anyone solve the problem using a different strategy?" The student uses the standard algorithm to solve the problem. The student said, "borrow from the 5 to make it a 4 and then I have 14." The teacher adds, "She had to borrow from the tens to get 14 ones." Another student showed their strategy (354 - 4 = 350; 350 - 3 = 347). The teacher adds, "You broke the 7 into smaller numbers (3 and 4)." Another student used an open number line and jumped back 7 places from 354.  

For the last activity of the lesson, the teacher said, "Partner A will read the expression (264 - 38) and represent the larger number using base ten blocks. Partner B will decide if you will decompose a ten and explain." The students are asked to use base ten blocks; however, the teacher does not provide the blocks.

9:31 Warm-Up
T: We’re going to add using mental math, 2 digit numbers. Ready?Heres the 1st one, let’s take a look. 65+20
About 10 hands in the air.
S: 85.
T: Who was thinking the same?
S: about 12 hands in the air.
T: Can you explain how you did that?
S: Well if you have 65 and add 10 you have 75. And then add another ten you get 85.
T: Rephrases….Here’s the next one. 85+1. What are we adding this time?
S: We’re adding a 1.
T: We’re adding a 1, which is a single-digit. …If you  have 85 and add 1 more…what will happen. Turn and whisper to your partner.
T: What’s the sum?
Chorally say 86 (most say it)
T: Next one …hmm. 65+20+1. Talk to your partner here.Wait, what do you notice, and what is the sum?
S: 3 pairs I can listen to are all talking about the math. One girls says this one shows the 65+20 like the first one, which is 85.
T: I heard lots of interesting things
S: Almost all raise their hands. . . .It was like the first equation 65+20. And then it used the second equation 85+1. 
T: It was like the two equations above. Anything to add, Javier?
J: It was like the same equation from the top. We know it’s 85 and then we know 85 + 1 = 86.
T: Stamps the key points both students share then says, “Can you believe we are doing this with mental math.” Reveals next problem. 65+21.
S: Eagerly talk and some say the answer is 86.
T: I actually heard some different discussion this time. Let’s talk about it.
S: I think the answer is 86.
T: Do we agree, show me some thumbs up or down.
S: All S but one have thumbs up.
T: Asks student to explain why they disagree.
S: Well they’re adding 21, which is a different number.
T: Does it look different than anything you see up here?
Some Ss say yea.
T: Yes, but do we see a connection with any of hte other equations? How did these help you with that one?
S: I know it was 86 because the 1 is not there (in the equation) but there’s the one (points to 21). 
T: Oh, so this one and the 20 are broken into different numbers, bu tin the next expression they’re together to make…what?
S: 21. 
T: Can we agree that 21 ist he same as 20+1? And that this equation is the same 65+21 and 65+20+1?
Some Ss say yes. …So really these two expressions, what do you notice about them?
A few hands go up.
S: THey’re the same.
T: Do they have the same value?
A few say yes.
T: We did not use any tools to solve these expressions, and every time we do mental math I get more impressed with your thinking and how you solve them.

k12_m_learning_goal:

k12_m_standards:
4.G.A.1
Draw points, lines, line segments, rays, angles (right, acute, obtuse), and perpendicular and parallel lines. Identify these in two-dimensional figures.

4.MD.C.5.a
An angle is measured with reference to a circle with its center at the common endpoint of the rays, by considering the fraction of the circular arc between the points where the two rays intersect the circle. An angle that turns through 1/360 of a circle is called a “one-degree angle,” and can be used to measure angles.

4.MD.C.6
Measure angles in whole-number degrees using a protractor. Sketch angles of specified measure.

11:30 T: That was tricky. I saw a lot of people doing this…demonstrates on board drawing a 2nd line kind of randomly. …How can I be more precise?…Let me use my protractor and find out…Who can help me line this up?
Lots of hands in the air
T: First of all, how can I tell these are perpendicular?
S: You want to line up the protractor..
T: Ok, but once I line up the protractor, if these are really perpendicular lines, what is that going to tell me?
A few hands go up.
S: That it’s a right angle?
T: Yes, right angle. 
S; Comes up to demonstrate and 3 Students look up while rest have eyes on their own paper.
T: Calls up S to line up angle again.
Most S are looking at their own paper. 
T; Who can come tell me how many degrees this angle is? 
6 hands up
T: First, which side am I reading from?
S: Right side. T: Why? S: Because…
T: Show me if you agree.
About 5 Ss put thumb up.
T: Because the angle over here opens to the right
S: comes up to read and with help, IDs its’ 98 degrees. 
T: Is this a right angle?
Some say no.
T: How can I make this a right angle? How can I make sure? 
One. Hand up.
T draws 1st line and says “What can I do?”
5 hands up.
T: Any idea of how I can use the protractor to make a right angle?
S: You can line up the protractor and put a dot on the 90.
T: Ok, can you come up and show us?
S: Goes up and makes a vertex on the line and says to 
T: Should we try this? Let’s try it. Add a vertex to your first line. Erase the other line if you made one.
T: So you’ve lined up your protractor ..give me a thumbs up if you did that (about 5 hands up)
T: Now I can Draw a dot right above the 90 degree mark. Now what should I do?
4 S hands up.
T; Draw your little dot right above the 90. What should I do now?
S; Draw a line from the dot to the vertex.
T: Should I draw it free-hand?
 Few say no.
T: What should I use?
S: The protractor.
T: The straight-edge of the protractor or a ruler. ,…Calls someone to board to demonstrate.
S lines up the ruler to create a straight line between the 2 points.
T: What did _ do?
S: He lined up the dot with the vertex?
T: Restates then draws the line to connect the two points, and then keeps going. “Try it.”

11:43 T: If we did this right, what should the angle be?
1/2 chorally say 90 degrees.
T: Ok, who can come up and measure for me?
Lots of hands up.
S comes up to place protractor. 
T: What did she do? Did she line this up properly?
A handful show agreement.
T: I agree. She lined it up properly. Who can read this angle for me?
S comes up to read it (same as before who struggled) and says “Exactly 90.”

Add within 100, including adding a two-digit number and a one-digit number, and adding a two-digit number and a multiple of 10, using concrete models or drawings and strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction; relate the strategy to a written method and explain the reasoning used. Solve multistep word problems posed with whole numbers and having whole-number answers using the four operations, including problems in which remainders must be interpreted. k12_m_ca2_notes:
For the first lesson activity, the teacher gives the students a word problem (Forty-five students are going on a field trip to a museum. Tickets for the museum are $18 each. Teachers have $900 to cover tickets for the trip. Will this be enough to cover tickets for every student? If yes, will there be any leftover money and how much? If no, how much more money is needed?). The teacher then asks, "Do you know what you will start with?" A student replies, "underline the important information." The teacher begins walking around to check for understanding and surface any misconceptions. 

The teacher walks to a student. The teacher asks, "I see you are working on an operation. How did you get to that?" The teacher then adds, "When you are done solving, will there be another step?" Some of her students were struggling, so she reread the problem to them as the students underlined important information. The teacher asked, "Is the question asking how much money is left over?" 

As the teacher continues to walk around, two students discuss how their work was different from each other. The student replies, "I did partial products and she did partial quotients." The teacher chose these students to solve their problem on the board. One student wrote her partial products on the board. For the student who used division to solve, the teacher asked, "Can you explain what you did here?" The student explains what she did to solve the problem using partial quotients. The teacher then asks, "How many used multiplication to solve?" Many of the students raised their hand. 

While the students are viewing the posters of the different strategies around the classroom, she pulls over a few students to review one of the strategies on the poster. The teacher says, "This one is using factors to solve the problem. They are doing (2 x 45) x 9." The teacher then adds, "You don't have to use this strategy, but it is another one." There were no further discussions with the strategies on the posters. Some of the students did not understand the strategy that was used on the poster to be able to say if it was the same or different.

k12_m_ca3_notes:
For the warm-up activity, the teacher asks, "Which expression does not belong? Make sure you explain why it doesn't belong. Talk to your partner." A student replies, "I think it is D (Expression: 3 x 3 x 10 x 5) because there is not a paratheses because not sure which one to do first." Another student replies, "A (Expression 5 x 90) because it is only one step and not multi-steps." The teacher adds, "that connects to what we are doing today with multi-step." A third student replies, "B (Expression: 90 + 90 + 90 + 90 + 90) because it is the only one with addition. The teacher adds, "We can switch it because it is the only one without multiplication." The teacher then asks, "What do they have in common?" A student replies, "All share the same answer." Another student replies, "Exact equation - written down differently. A is an equation. B - D is breaking it down so they are easier to solve." 

For the second lesson activity, the students are asked to walk around to 5 posters that have strategies on how other people solved the problem about the field trip to the museum. The teacher asked, "Which strategy is most similar to yours? What is different from your strategy?" The teacher walks around to the groups of students and asks if it is similar to or different than their strategy. A student replies, "His is different because I used partial products." 

For the last activity of the lesson, the students were asked to complete this word problem (Movie tickets are $9 each. The theater sold the same number of tickets two days in a row. The theater made $3,132 from ticket sales on the first day. 1. Record and answer one question of your choice from the list the class generated. Discuss your strategy with your partner. Use the given information about movie tickets to complete the following statement: __________ tickets were sold on the first and second days. The students come up with 2 questions: (1) How much money did they make on both days? (2) How many people bought tickets on the first day? Both days? The students were given time to answer on of the questions generated from the class. The teacher asks, "How many people bought tickets on the first day?" A student comes up to the board to show her work using division ($3,132 divided by 9). The student seemed to struggle with completing the problem; however, she found her mistake and was able to self-correct herself. However, the teacher explains her thinking instead of asking the student to explain.

1:55 Yesterday we practiced adding numbers. Thumbs up
Warm-up: How many do you see: Too many tens. You’re gonna look and see how many you see
T slowly scrolls down. 
Almost all hands up for 1st one. T: How many did you, see W?
S: 287. I saw 2 hundreds, 80 tens..8 tens, and 7 ones.
T: writes on chart paper and give me a me too if you agree. ..I see some disagree. H what did you see?
H: I saw 2 hundreds, 8 tens, and 8 ones
T: Give me a me too if you agree (about 7 show)...Ok, i’m going to show you again. …Reads it again and says, what H right?
Most verbally say Yes.
T: How many do you see and how do you see them? (380)...Ready?
Almost all hands up
S: I saw 380.
T: how did you see them?
S: I saw 3 hundred, i saw 7 tens, 5 on top and 2 on the bottom, there was 7 ones on top and 3 on the bottom. And then I composed the ones.
T: Question, how mamy of you saw the 5 tens and thought that’s 50 and I don’t need to count this. About 7 kids agree. T: Just curious,, let’s see.
T shows problem again and shows S was right. 
T shows next one; 426 - 3 hs, 12 ts, 6 ones
Almost all hands up
J: 426.
T: how did you se them?
J: 3 hundreds, 12 tens?..T: how many were in each…J: 5 on the t0p, 5 in the middle, and 2 on the bottom. T: and how many ones. J: 3 on top and 3 in the middle
T: What’s your strategy for keeping track of all these?
S: I slide those over (inaudible)

k12_ela_standards: RI.4.5: Describe the overall structure (e.g., chronology, comparison, cause/effect, problem/solution) of events, ideas, concepts, or information in a text or part of a text.

k12_ela_ca1_notes:
The text of the lesson is from the Wonders Curriculum. It is titled "A World Without Rules."

This lesson was a review of what was completed another day. The teacher indicated she wanted to review cause and effect. When looking at the student workbooks, the students had previously completed the questions that went along with this text.
k12_ela_ca2a: 2- Few questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 2- Few questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 2- Vocabulary questions and tasks rarely focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 1- Questions and tasks seem random and are not intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: The teacher begins the lesson by wanting the students to compare and contrast 2 different pictures. Then, the teacher asks, "Who can tell me what the purpose is for reading this text? A student replies, "What the world would be like without rules." The class discusses a cause and effect relationship with rules and without rules. The teacher randomly asks the students a question about latin root and prefix (It is the next question in the student workbook). The teacher then asks, Why is "Back to Reality" a good title for this section?" However, the class does not reread the section. A student replies, "Because we are back to a world with rules." Towards the end of the lesson, the teacher asks students to discuss the words (darted, phoned, dragging, trapping, helping, cared) and asks a suffix question. The order of the questions are very random, and there was confusion on what was the purpose of the lesson.

Throughout the lesson, the teacher is consistently having the redirect the students because of their behavior. The classroom management needs to be addressed. I assume some of the behavior concerns are from discussing/completing questions that were previously discussed. 

One example of a student referring to the text when providing an answer. The teacher asks, "What does eventually mean and how is it used in the text? A student replies "Eventually means the end." Another student replies, "The way it is used in the text, what it means for eventually like finally he wondered down the stairs to his brother." 

The students are not encouraged to discuss the questions with each other. They seem to not be able to have a discussion with each other about the text. From my observations, the teacher asks a question. A few students will respond (sometimes it is the same students responding). Then, the teacher will ask another question. There is no connections between the types of questions. Also, the teacher does not adapt the lesson based on the students' needs.

The purpose of this lesson is for students to find all of the compositions and decompositions of 10 in the context of a story problem.

Compose and decompose 10 in multiple ways.
k12_m_standards:
K.CC.B.4.c
Understand that each successive number name refers to a quantity that is one larger.

K.OA.A.1
Represent addition and subtraction with objects, fingers, mental images, drawingsDrawings need not show details, but should show the mathematics in the problem. (This applies wherever drawings are mentioned in the Standards.), sounds (e.g., claps), acting out situations, verbal explanations, expressions, or equations.

K.OA.A.2
Solve addition and subtraction word problems, and add and subtract within 10, e.g., by using objects or drawings to represent the problem.

K.OA.A.3
Decompose numbers less than or equal to 10 into pairs in more than one way, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record each decomposition by a drawing or equation.

K.OA.A.4
For any number from 1 to 9, find the number that makes 10 when added to the given number, e.g., by using objects or drawings, and record the answer with a drawing or equation.

k12_m_ca2_notes:
For the warm-up activity, the students were asked to find the value of each expression. 
4 + 1 = 
The teacher asks, "What does this symbol mean?" The student reply, "Plus." The teacher ask, "Do we only count both sides or just one side?" Most students respond, "Both sides." These questions were asked for the other expression as well (5 + 1, 8 - 1, 7 - 1). For each expression, the teacher wrote the picture and found the answer. 

During the lesson launch activity, the teacher is walking around to check student's understanding. Some of the responses the teacher said to the students were: "I love your dots." "Can you show me how you got your answer? Make sure you show your work." 

For the center activity towards the end of the lesson, the students are provided with 10 yellow and red counters. The teacher said, "We are going to use the counters and shake and roll. Count the yellow and red counters." The group of 4 students were only given 1 cup with counters to use.

k12_m_ca3_notes:
For the launch activity, the students are asked to solve this problem:  There are 6 pigeons in the fountain. There are 4 pigeons on the bench. How many pigeons are there? Show your thinking with objects, drawings, numbers, or words.
The teacher asked, "Are we subtracting or adding?" Most of the students replied, "Adding." The teacher asked, "What are we adding?" Some of the students replied, "6 + 4." The questions did not dig deeper than just the answer - not asking "Why" or "How do you know." The students are asked to turn and talk to their partner about their work. The teacher asked, "What does the 6 and 4 represent?" A student replied, "How many pigeons." The teacher asked, "How did we get that answer (6 + 4 = 10)?" 

The students are then asked to solve this problem:  There were 10 pigeons. Some of the pigeons were in the fountain. The rest of the pigeons were on the bench. How many of the pigeons were in the fountain? Then how many of the pigeons were on the bench? Show your thinking with objects, drawings, numbers, or words. 
The teacher asked, "How many pigeons were on the bench?" A student replied, "We don't know." The teacher asked, "Can we think about all the ways to make ten? An easy way can just be to draw 10 objects." The teacher called on individual students to make equations with 10, as she drew a line to separate the objects into two groups (0 + 10, 1 + 9, etc.). The teacher did not provide much of an opportunity to allow the students to productively struggle or share each other's thinking. 

The students are then asked to look at a ten frame problem. The teacher asked, "Can anyone give me an equation for this ten frame?" A student replied, "9 + 1 = 10." The teacher asked, "Can anyone explain why it is 9 +1 = 10?" A student replied, "Because there are 9 that are red and 1 that is yellow." The students had a similar discussion for the B-Tool strategy.

T: Can everybody please pause.  Open your packet to problem 3.1  I had a few questions on this one so I want to go over it.  This was a proof that we did together.  What type of decimal is it?
S: Irrational
T: No, why type of decimal?
S: Never ending
T: But what type of never ending?
S: Repeated
T: Repeated and you know that from the bar.  What does that mean?
S: It’s the same number over and over again.
T: What type of number?  Rational or irrational?  What does it mean?
S: You could turn it into a fraction.
T: We can turn any repeating decimal into a fraction by doing this.  First we let our variable x equal our repeating decimal.  Now, we want at least one digit in front of the decimal place.  So we are going to multiply both sides by 10.  Remember when you multiply by 10 it changes the place value by one spot.  Modeled on board The next step is we subtract an x from both sides.  We know x is equal to 0.13 repeating.  So now we can have 9x on this side if we subract from this side we’d be left with 1.2.  Then we divide both sides by 9.  X = 1.2 divided by 9.  You need to remember that repeating decimals are rational numbers.  
S: Where did you get the 9 from?
T: Remember our inverse operations?  Explained answer


T: Let’s look at the back page.  I want to talk about the negative square root of 100.  Is this rational or irrational?
S: Rational
T: How do you know?  Who could explain why it’s rational?
S: Because the square root of negative 100 is 10.  
T: Is it just 10?
S: Negative 10
T: Why?
S: Because there is a negative out there
T: Who can explain why this can still be a negative?
S: As long as you can write it as a fraction.
T: How can you write negative 10 as a fraction?
S: You put one over ten.  
T: Does negative ten equal one tenth?

k12_m_learning_goal: Add and subtract within 100 using strategies based on place value, including composing and decomposing a ten, and the properties of operations.
k12_m_standards:
2.NBT.B.5
Fluently add and subtract within 100 using strategies based on place value, properties of operations, and/or the relationship between addition and subtraction.
k12_m_ca1a: Yes- The enacted lesson focuses only on mathematics within the grade-level/ course-level standards.
k12_m_ca1b: Yes- The enacted lesson builds on students’ prior skills and understandings.
k12_m_ca1c: Yes- The enacted lesson explicitly targets the aspect(s) of Rigor called for by the standard(s) being addressed.
k12_m_ca1_notes: The students were familiar with and mostly used the base ten blocks to subtract or add. The teacher began the lesson by saying, "We are going to review what we are going over in this unit, which is the different ways to add and subtract. When you add and subtract, you can use base ten blocks, number lines, or breaking it up into hundreds, tens, and ones."
k12_m_ca2a: 2- Instruction is limited to showing students how to get the answer.
k12_m_ca2b: 2- Student solution methods are shared, but few connections are made to strengthen student understanding.
k12_m_ca2c: 2- There are few checks for understanding, or the progress of only a few students is assessed. Instruction is not adjusted based on students’ needs.
k12_m_ca2d: 1- The lesson includes no summary of the mathematics.
k12_m_ca2_notes:
The teacher said the first problem, "36 + 47." She called on a student to solve the problem on the board. (This part of the lesson was a continuation from the day before.) The student drew the base ten blocks for both numbers; however, was struggling to solve the problem. The teacher asked, "I have a question: if you are adding, are you going to draw base ten blocks for both numbers or one number." The teacher proceeds to help the student. The teacher asked, "How many of you got 83?" Some students raised their hand. The teacher then asks, "If you put them together, which one do you count first, the tens or the ones?" The student at the board said, "Ones." However, the student at the board does not show their thinking of how they got the answer 83 and does not share it with the class. 

The teacher uses sticks to call on students to show their work, instead of strategically choosing students' solution methods. 

While the students are solving the problems, the teacher is walking around, observing the student's work. The teacher is asking questions, such as: "Do you add or subtract here?" "You tell me - asking students to show their work." "Write the equation."

k12_m_ca3_notes:
The teacher moves on to the following problems (77 - 10, 77 - 20, and 90 - 70). The teacher reads the directions (Find the value of each difference). The teacher asks, "Does difference mean to add or subtract?" Most of the students reply, "Subtract."

The teacher calls on a student to come to the board to solve 77 - 10. The student's answer is 67; however, he does not explain his thinking to the class. The teacher asked, "How many got 67?" The teacher also asked, "How many added instead of subtracted?" 

The students begin working on 77 - 20. The teacher chooses a stick for a student to come solve the problem on the board. One student seemed to try to use their base ten blocks to help them solve them problem. The student starts to solve the problem on the board, but he seems to be struggling. The teacher asked, "You are drawing what?" The student replies, "7 tens." The teacher asked, "How many ones are in 77?" The student replied, "7." The teacher asked, "How many tens are you taking away?" The student replies, "2." The student says, "77 - 20 = 57." 

The teacher gives too much time between solving each problem, which causes some students to be a disturbance to others.
