fsot_1:
Curriculum: Really Great Reading
Lesson 3
Topic: Vowel Consonant E
fsot_targeted_skills:
RF.K.3.B: Associate the long and short sounds with the five major vowel graphemes (a,e,i,o,u), using open and closed syllable types ( e.g., open-go, closed-got).

RF.K.2: Demonstrate understanding of spoken words, syllables, and sounds (phonemes)
fsot_ac1_notes:
The teacher starts the lesson by explaining the goal of the lesson. She is reviewing the 3 types of vowels – short vowels, long vowels, and R controlled vowels. The teacher asks the students about each type of vowel. The class gives a coral response to each question. The teacher said, “Short vowel says the…”. The students respond, “Sound.” The teacher asked, “Long vowel says the…”. The students respond, “Letter name.” Then she asked the sounds of the different vowels. It appears that all students are participating in the questions. The teacher then asks the students about the R controlled vowels and the students knew exactly what to sing. They then discussed the difference between a phoneme and a grapheme. The students had a short song to sing to describe the difference. 

The teacher reviews what the students have been working on all week. The students have been working on the vowel consonant e. The teacher then continues to review material: diagraphs, trigraphs, blend, open syllable, closed syllable). The student provide a coral respond to each of these.
fsot_td_notes:
The teacher then begins Lesson 3 of Really Great Reading. The students watched a video about vowel consonant e pattern. From the lesson video, it seems that the students then built words using word tiles. I’m not sure what the directions were for this activity. 

The students were given a list of words to sound out. The teacher said, “We are going to use our phoneme knowledge to sound out these words.” There words were: mad, pet, pin, not, cub. From the video, I can see a student using his fingers to count the phonemes. Then the teacher said, “We are going to use these same words, but we are going to add the vowel consonant e this time.” The students were asked to get their kits with letter tiles out. They were asked to find all of their vowels. The students were asked to build the word mad on their board. Above the word, they have the color tiles. The teacher then said, “Now we are going to add the vowel consonant e to the word mad. Now we are going to sound it out as a team.” The teacher then reviews the understanding of the “sneaky e” making it a long vowel. Then the students built the word pet on their board, and then they were asked to add the vowel consonant e to the word pet (it made the word Pete).

Students were given 10 minutes to write independently using those stems to reflect on one of the previously read text of their choice.  The teacher circulated and monitored employing checks for understanding as well as supporting students who needed additional help such as providing visual vocabulary sheets and providing access to the copy of the book since students did not have their own copy of texts. fsot_1: Module 7/ Lesson 1/ HMH :: tricksters and tales
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher delivered lesson from module 7 lesson 1 with a focus on tricksters and tales which follows the grade four scope and sequence.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher hooks students for lesson 1 with highly engaging questions to discuss such as “what trickster tales or tall tales have you read before?” Teacher asks students to turn to page 75 to review quote “there is magic to storytelling” by Lynn Collins and discuss their interpretation of the quote and if they agree/disagree. Teacher also asks students to share lessons they've learned in their own lives or from previous stories they've read.
fsot_sp_notes: Most student engage in oral tasks including turn and talks, interpretation of quotes via student notebook, sharing out lessons they've learned in their lives such "don't judge a book by its cover" and "whats done in the dark always come to light". Most students did get to share but not all and most students engage in the turn and talk about tell tales they have read about or have been passed down from family members but not all are able to contribute. Students are also asked to listen to a read aloud via smart board of Little Red Riding Hood towards the end of the lesson.
fsot_ad_notes: There was no evidence of formal data collection but informal data was collected when students shared out their responses and teacher refined or clarified their answers and asked them to elaborate on their meanings.

A: Examples are used to make the mathematics of the lesson clear. For example, T: Use Andre’s way to find the value of 189-73. Show your thinking. Use a number line if it helps. 
S: I’ve finished. 
T: Try it a different strategy to see if you get the same answer. 
T: how did you do this? Did you use mental math?
S: yes
B: Student solution methods are shared and some connections are made. For example, Another student goes to the board to show how the two problems connect
T: S what did you notice or wonder.
S: I notice that Jada used the base ten blocks and Andre used the number line.
S: So the x’s, we started with 375 and the x’s are showing the answer of 351.
T: why are these crossed off?
C: There are checks for understanding, however an actual change in instruction only happened once.  For example, S: I think if I add 500 that might work because 5 +5 is 10
T: hmm that’s good thinking. But look at that tens place what’s there? What will happen if add another 500 will it be more than 1000?
S: oh yeah
T: So what are we going to do?
T: hmm, I’m thinking, thinking thinking
T: Asks certain pairs of student to start to talk about their thinking. 
12:18: Student comes to board and writes answers.
S: I respectfully disagree on 2 and 4. The teacher and students then began to discuss problems 2 and 4. 
D: Not Observed

fsot_ac1_notes: Guided reading aligned to current reading data. Direct teacher-student coaching on decoding, sound combos, sight words, blends, and chunking. Students must retell the book they read independently and answer an inferential questions.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher constantly has high energy for phonics drills & GR instruction. All student books are aligned to current instructional reading level. Teacher consistently prompts self-reliance with decoding and blending unknown words.
fsot_sp_notes: Students are reading on instructional reading level. Students are required to read decodable text at their level each day, with direct teacher coaching. Students do no have to apply to writing, only conversational engagement. Students participate mainly with teacher (less with peers), and participate in group conversation to retell the book and answer the inferential question.

fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher has aligned guided reading instruction to the instructional reading level of each child.

Teacher moves at an urgent pace and ensures 100% participation and accountability throughout (all students required to read the text independently and participate in the retell/inference discussion).

fsot_ad_notes: Teacher actively collects data on individual reading data (decoding, fluency); does not collect informal data on comprehension. No group adjustments or feedback on comprehension.

During the language dive, teachers references how might the part of the sentence "so many" change the meaning of the sentence if it wasn't there. Try's to lead students to the understanding of the authors reasoning behind including "so many". Students struggle to see the difference between the sentence with "so many" in it and with the sentence without "so many" because there is no visual for them to compare and contrast it to.

k12_ela_ca3_notes: While teacher is reading and talking about/pointing out the different purposes for birds feathers, students are not doing anything, some are listening but some are not focused and distracted. There is no student product for students to apply their learning or have a productive struggle that is aligned to determining the main idea of the reading. Teacher transitions to the language dive discussion but there are no visuals for the students to reference besides the sentence in question which is "That's because feathers have so many jobs to do." Teacher asks students to turn and talk but most students struggle to understand how the sentence would change meaning if "so many" was taken away from the sentence which does not lead to a productive struggle but to students becoming frustrated and lose interest. One student shares out that the author includes "so many" to show how many different things the feathers can do, and if it was in the sentence then it could mean that the feathers only do one thing. This connection was not made by the rest of the class and the teacher did not take the opportunity to build upon the students statement to help the other students get to that thinking.

T: We are going to do the first few together.  

C: The teacher did not provide opportunities for the students to explain their thinking. 
D: The one opportunity the teacher provided for students to talk to each other about mathematics was not well timed and students became distracted.  For example: T: You are going to work together and complete how Tyler and Clare would complete the problem.
Teacher divided up the students. 
Students began working on the problems. 
Students are talking with each other about the problems and how they compare. (4 minutes)
Too much time was given to work the problem, students were all over the room. And not doing math. 1 kid reading, three kids coloring, 4 kids talking about other stuff other than math, two without partners not doing math. This lasted for 3 minutes. 

E; The teacher provided some opportunities to connect the language of mathematics with students' informal language.  She helped students understand decompose and use it correctly.

ipg_rubric: K-12: ELA/Literacy IPG (please use this tool for K-2 observations that are not focused on foundational skills)
k12_ela/literacy_1: EL/Module 4/Unit 1 lesson 1: How people enjoy trees
k12_ela_lg:
I can observe how people and characters enjoy trees. 
I can describe how people and characters enjoy trees.
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: The book Gus is a Tree is aligned to the EL curriculum. The book provides students with examples of how people might enjoy trees, which is part of the learning target. Teacher does a read aloud, provides students time to discuss the book during stopping points and teacher points out important takeaways and ideas.
k12_ela_ca2a: 2- Few questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 2- Few questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 2- Vocabulary questions and tasks rarely focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 2- Few questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes: Most questions are low inference, what do you see, what does the word drift mean, what does pleasant mean, with no connection to how those words are used in the text or connection to what it is helping them understand? A question that referenced evidence from the text was " How do we know that Gus loves trees? Students reply "because he's hugging them", they had to refer to the text and infer meaning to his actions because the text does not explicitly say that Gus loves trees.
k12_ela_ca3a: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.
k12_ela_ca3b: 2- Teacher provides some opportunities, and some students take them.
k12_ela_ca3c: 2- Teacher provides some opportunities, and some students take them.
k12_ela_ca3d: 2- Teacher provides some opportunities, and some students take them.
k12_ela_ca3e: 2- Teacher provides some opportunities, and some students take them.
k12_ela_ca3f: 2- Teacher provides some opportunities, and some students take them.
k12_ela_ca3_notes: Teacher provides students with 2 opportunities to discuss with their peers, once in the beginning prior to reading to brainstorm ways people can enjoy trees and at the end to discuss what they found interesting about the book. Teacher utilizes discussion as a language strategy and during that time she walks around with a checklist listening in on student conversations.

fsot_ac1_notes: '-Teacher and students both demonstrated clear evidence of familarity with phonics routines. slideshow and materials were accessible and curriculum was implemented with fidelity.
fsot_td_notes:
'-Teacher directed instruction was accurate and explicit. 
Teacher asked variety of questions and made clear statements to drive thinking and instruction "This word has a vowel team and a digraph" "Which word up here has a final blend?" "Where does my mouth go when I say /mp/? Try it." Which word might...?"
fsot_sp_notes:
'-Lesson was whole group and teacher prompted students to practice skills multiple times. Students were asked to repeat words, stand up and act them out, say parts of words aloud
-Most students were meeting teacher expectation
-Teacher used mianly whole group participation but did also call on 1-2 volunteers.
-Students could benefit from stronger materials to support instruction (anchor chart co created instead of a slide)
fsot_ad_notes:
'-There was no evidence of formal data collection, however teacher modified instruction and pacing based on questioning. When students demonstrated confusion on generating -lk words (ie one student said look) teacher slowed down instruction and used chart paper to clarify. 
-Would like to see additional evidence of differentiation

fsot_1: HMH Into Reading: Foundational Skills Block
fsot_targeted_skills: '-SWBAT identify and sort words that begin with s-constant blends (st, sp, sl, sn)
fsot_ac1_notes:
'-Lesson was directly following the scope and sequence of HMH: FS curriculum
-Materials, instruction and objectives were aligned to scope and sequence of program for kinder.
fsot_td_notes:
'-Teacher is dual language, ENL speaker, so there were some inaccuracies in the pronunciation of sounds or the meaning of words. Classroom is dual language.
-Teacher led whole group activity sorting words with s-blends. Sorting was accurate and teacher asked students to repeat each word to sort in the anchor chart.
-Teacher led small group instruction using decodable text based on data. Instruction in this group was accurate and explicit.
fsot_sp_notes:
'-Observer noted two areas of student practice: 1. Whole Group instruction and 2. Stations and Small Groups
1. WGI: Lesson had students participate by repeating words. However, teacher sorted the words and did the thinking for students (As opposed to having students share where they thought the word should go)
2. SGI: This practice was high quality. There were multiple stations based on letters, sounds, decodable texts, and a teacher led group which prioritized student practice with decoding with automaticity.
fsot_ad_notes:
'-Although the observation did not have direct evidence of teacher data, stations and groups were built from data and strongly differentiated. 
-1 group was working with letter/sound 1, 1 group had a scaffolded task that aligned with the daily objective, teacher group was practicing on decodable text that appeared to directly align with their proximal development. Overall, multiple examples of differentiation for student practice.

k12_m_learning_goal:
Represent and solve two-step problems involving multiplication and division. 
I can represent and solve two-step problems involving multiplication and division.
k12_m_standards:
CC.3.OA.1 Represent and solve problems involving multiplication and division. Interpret products of whole numbers, e.g., interpret 5 × 7 as the total number of objects in 5 groups of 7 objects each. For example, describe a context in which a total number of objects can be expressed as 5 × 7.
CC.3.OA.2 Represent and solve problems involving multiplication and division. Interpret whole-number quotients of whole numbers, e.g., interpret 56 ÷ 8 as the number of objects in each share when 56 objects are partitioned equally into 8 shares, or as a number of shares when 56 objects are partitioned into equal shares of 8 objects each. For example, describe a context in which a number of shares or a number of groups can be expressed as 56 ÷ 8.
CC.3.OA.8 Solve problems involving the four operations, and identify and explain patterns in arithmetic. Solve two-step word problems using the four operations. Represent these problems using equations with a letter standing for the unknown quantity. Assess the reasonableness of answers using mental computation and estimation strategies including rounding.

CC.4.NF.3c Add and subtract mixed numbers with like denominators, e.g., by replacing each mixed number with an equivalent fraction, and/or by using properties of operations and the relationship between addition and subtraction.
CC.4.NF.3d Solve word problems involving addition and subtraction of fractions referring to the same whole and having like denominators, e.g., by using visual fraction models and equations to represent the problem.

k12_ela/literacy_1: EL/ Module 4/Unit 2/ Lesson 2/ Reading, Speaking and Listening: Focused read aloud: A Tree is Nice
k12_ela_lg: I can identify and discuss the reasons an author gives to support points in A Tree Is Nice.
k12_ela_standards: (RI.K.1, RI.K.2, RI.K.4, RI.K.6, RI.K.8, SL.K.1a, SL.K.6)
k12_ela_ca1a: Yes - The lesson is focused on  a text or multiple texts.
k12_ela_ca1b: Yes- The anchor text(s) are at or above both the qualitative and quantitative complexity expected for the grade and time in the school year.
k12_ela_ca1c: Yes- The text(s) exhibits exceptional craft and thought and/or provides meaningful information in the service of building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca1_notes: Teacher does a chunked read a loud of the book, has stopping points to stamp ideas and ask students questions referring to the events that show how trees are nice and can be helpful. Students are able to take the events in the story and explain why trees are nice to have. Teacher takes student responses and puts them on a chart for students to see and reference.
k12_ela_ca2a: 3- Many questions and tasks attend to the qualitative features of the text to build understanding.
k12_ela_ca2b: 3- Many questions and tasks require students to cite evidence from the text.
k12_ela_ca2c: 1- No questions and tasks focus students on the words that matter most and how they are used in the text.
k12_ela_ca2d: 3- Some questions and tasks are intentionally sequenced to support building knowledge.
k12_ela_ca2_notes:
Teacher asks the students questions to build their understanding of purpose people might want to plant trees or ways people use trees. The teacher has the students refer back to the text in order to make those connections.
 T: What is this person doing under this tree?
S: They are sleeping
T: What is this person doing?
S: Swinging
T: Yes swinging which is another way we can enjoy a tree
T: Have you ever sat under a tree on a hot day to get some shade?
S: Yes
T: So that is another reason why we plant trees?
S:for shade
T: lets add that to our chart
T: What are these people doing down here?
S: The grandma is sitting
T: There are many ways we can enjoy trees, someone is climbing trees, resting under trees
S: Its just a house
T: Lets read
T: Why is it nice for a tree to be by a house?
S: It keeps the house nice and cool
T: What is this picture showing us?
S: Snow
T: It could be snow and it looks very windy, how does the tree help the house?
S: The tree helps the house and the roof
k12_ela_ca3a: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.
k12_ela_ca3b: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.
k12_ela_ca3c: 2- Teacher provides some opportunities, and some students take them.
k12_ela_ca3e: 2- Teacher provides some opportunities, and some students take them.
k12_ela_ca3_notes: Teachers provides opportunities for students to interact with the text through specific questioning where the students must refer to the text or utilize the illustrations to answer the questions. k12_m_learning_goal: Learning Goal: I can solve various problems involving circles.
k12_m_standards: Standard: 7.G.B.4 Know the formulas for the area and circumference of a circle and use them to solve problems; give an informal derivation of the relationship between the circumference and area of a circle.
k12_m_ca1a: Yes- The enacted lesson focuses only on mathematics within the grade-level/ course-level standards.
k12_m_ca1b: Yes- The enacted lesson builds on students’ prior skills and understandings.
k12_m_ca1c: Yes- The enacted lesson explicitly targets the aspect(s) of Rigor called for by the standard(s) being addressed.
k12_m_ca1_notes: The teacher addresses all aspects of rigor targeted by the standard for this learning target. The teacher reviews the procedure for calculating circumference and areas of circles and uses real-world contexts to apply the skills.
k12_m_ca2a: 4- A variety of instructional techniques and examples are used to make the mathematics of the lesson clear.
k12_m_ca2b: 3- Student solution methods are shared, and some mathematical connections are made between them.
k12_m_ca2c: 3- There are checks for understanding used throughout the lesson to assess progress of some students; minimal adjustments are made to instruction, even when adjustments are appropriate.
k12_m_ca2_notes:
Throughout the lesson, the teacher employs instructional practices that allow all students to learn the lesson's content.

For example, she explicitly models the tasks, states her thinking out loud, and demonstrates the steps used to solve the tasks. The teacher explicitly models the solution steps to the Do Now problems, an "I Do" and "We Do" problem. For example, "They are telling me that the circumference is 50pi, so I need to use this information to determine my diameter; now I need to find my area in terms of pi. My radius, as you told me, will be "half." Additionally, she demonstrates to students how to use the calculator effectively. 

As students work on tasks, she circulates the room and checks for students understanding. The teacher tries to assess common misconceptions, saying, "The blank is something I noticed you struggle with. Then, she adjusts instructions to address them. For example, the teacher reinforces, "You need to leave your answer in terms of "pi" after acknowledging that is a common misconception. 

The teacher requests students to share their interpretations of the problems and solution methods. Then, throughout the class, the teacher solicits students' responses and references students' work when she summarizes her observations.

k12_m_ca3c: 4- Teacher provides many opportunities, and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3e: 3- Teacher provides many opportunities, and some students take them; or teacher provides some opportunities and most students take them.
k12_m_ca3_notes:
The teacher allows all students to exhibit mathematical practices while engaging with the lesson's content.

During the start of the class, students are given time to answer a question demonstrating their understanding of the formula for the area of a circle. Additionally, students are given more opportunities during guided practice after the teacher explicitly models. Later, the teacher provides students with opportunities to work on problems independently. 

The teacher does ask students questions that prompt their thinking, conceptually and about the procedural steps. For example, “What is the radius, in centimeters, of a circle with a circumference of 28pi centimeters?” Or, “How did you get that, sir?" Yes, by dividing that by 2." After reading a word problem, the teacher asks, “What information do you need when calculating the circumference of a circle?” Student answers, “Circle” She replies, “You need the circle, yes. But what specific information is needed?” After reading another problem, the teacher pushes the students to dissect the main idea and offer solution steps. For example, the teacher asks, “What exactly are we calculating from this problem? The circumference or the area?”Once students offer the solution to calculations, she asks, “Are we done? Is this the full solution to the problem?” “Do we have to leave our answer in terms of pi?” She continues to probe, “What exactly are we calculating here?” “What does this number represent?” “Yes, this represents seeds.” “So, how would we apply this?”

The teacher encourages students to use specific mathematical language, including area, circumference, diameter, and radius. The teacher encourages students to verbalize the difference between these terms and reference them when discussing their solutions.

k12_m_learning_goal:
I can change an expression with a negative exponent into an equivalent expression with a positive exponent.
I can choose an appropriate exponent rule to rewrite an expression with a single exponent.
k12_m_standards: Standard: 8.EE.A.1: Know and apply the properties of integer exponents to generate equivalent numerical expressions.
k12_m_ca1a: Yes- The enacted lesson focuses only on mathematics within the grade-level/ course-level standards.
k12_m_ca1b: Yes- The enacted lesson builds on students’ prior skills and understandings.
k12_m_ca1c: Yes- The enacted lesson explicitly targets the aspect(s) of Rigor called for by the standard(s) being addressed.
k12_m_ca2a: 4- A variety of instructional techniques and examples are used to make the mathematics of the lesson clear.
k12_m_ca2b: 1- Student solution methods are not shared.
k12_m_ca2c: 4- There are checks for understanding used throughout the lesson to assess progress of all students, and adjustments to instruction are made in response, as needed.
k12_m_ca2_notes:
After the entry assignment, the teacher reviews the exponent rules in preparation for their independent and guided practice work, demonstrating “(3^2)^4 = 3^2 * 3^2 * 3^2 * 3^2” on the board.

Additionally,  after each task that students are given, the teacher reviews the exponent rules. For example, “You will add the exponents since the base is the same.”
Although the teacher solicits students' responses throughout the lesson, the teacher does not share students’ work.
The teacher circulates and gives students intentional feedback as students work in small groups. For instance, “Do you realize what this means?” “You should add the exponents, right? So, should it be 8 + 3?”

After recognizing common misconceptions, the teacher addressed them during his review. For instance, “Here is where you guys tend to get confused.” “When you have different bases, you can neither add the exponents nor these. I want you to notice the difference between these examples (as the teacher points to references on the board).” Additionally, the teacher encourages students to use a set of parentheses when simplifying expressions after recognizing that this step may benefit them.

k12_m_ca3_notes:
Students were given an entry assignment and allowed to work in small groups to practice using the exponent rule. “Choose 6 of the equations to write using a single exponent.” Students were also given time to engage in a cool-down and tasked to rewrite expressions using a single, positive exponent. More than 40% of the class time was dedicated to student practice. 
The teacher does encourage students to struggle productively but not effectively. For example, after recognizing that students were not actively engaged in the entry assignment, the teacher needs to do more to refocus them or address their misconceptions, which may fill in their gaps of misunderstanding and then allow them to preserve. 
Additionally, the teacher asks students to perform an error analysis during one instance. However, the teacher needs to give students more time to process. Therefore, they need help to struggle effectively. After a few seconds of introducing the problem, the teacher asks for students' responses. 
The teacher prompts students to think about the math content throughout the lesson by asking them questions. For example, “What do we do with the exponents when we have the same base?” However, many questions only push students to think about the procedure, not necessarily driving conceptual understanding.

Students have opportunities to support teacher in building words via spelling and proper pronunciation of letters and sounds were emphasized throughout i.e.- "help me spell snack-- s n (what’s our blend? What should we put at the end for our k sound? Ck!!)". During the we do students practice writing their own captions alongside the teacher and via the you do they do so by themselves.

Teacher provides time for students to practice out of context via writing but can grow in the area of providing different opportunities to work out of context via movement or puzzles. Students do not engage in decodable text for this lesson.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher adjusts instruction accordingly as noted via materials prepared for students and informally based on the turn and talk. If students did not correctly share an opinion sentence teacher clarified and adjusted instruction. Formal data collection was not noted.

fsot_1: EL Module 4, cycle 21, lessons 106 - mystery words
fsot_targeted_skills: I can follow along with a poem. I can identify three mystery words.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher delivers lesson from EL  skills grade K module in alignment with curriculum scope and sequence.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher delivers lesson in child friendly manner reading poem with enthusiasm and incorporates music to introduce the new mystery words. Teacher gives "light bulbs" to participants who are on task to praise them. Instruction from teacher is not always clear and there are a few behavioral disruptions to attend to that cause interruption from the learning target. Students do make meaning from listening via the poem read aloud and are asked What can we do to help ourselves get the high frequency words in our memories? How will that help us with reading or writing? but responses from students show mixed results.
fsot_sp_notes: Students have opportunities to work out of context via mystery words when the teacher rotates her small groups. Students work with worksheets and puzzles to identify them, write them in sentences, trace them etc. The words included one and all. Most students participate in the lesson-- a few need reminders to get on task/ participate.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher prepares materials based on data to support small groups and inserts two CFUs during lesson. Formal data or checklist are not employed.

direct_to_ts_obs: End of year (last observation of the year)
fsot_targeted_skills: I can demonstrate my understanding of spelling key terms via mid module assessment.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher delivers EL cycle 23 spelling assessment which follows a grade level scope and sequence for collecting mid module data.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher delivers spelling assessment in child friendly manner by requiring students to clap out syllables and tap out their words before writing. Students all practice listening via dictation and then recording their responses on the worksheet. The spelling assessment increases in difficulty as it goes on. Words included ate, even, funny, ladies, rotate, alone, animal, decode, congratulate, incomplete. 80% of students spelled 7/10 words accurately-- congratulate, ladies, and incomplete posed some difficulty.
fsot_sp_notes: Students all participate in the lesson are asked to write a sentence to apply these skills :: "We’re taking our bunny to the party in the garden". This posed some difficulty for students but they perservered. Few students work in the context of decodable text via Lexia but primarily just engage with the worksheet.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher frequently collects data via assessment and by pulling students 1:1 to determine their progress thus far. Students are also on Lexia based on their reading level on computers to aid in their reading growth while small group instruction takes place.

fsot_targeted_skills: I can fix sentences using r controlled vowels.
fsot_ac1_notes: Teacher delivers grade 1 lesson from EL skills module/ curriculum scope and sequence.
fsot_td_notes: Teacher delivers grade level 1 r controlled vowel lesson in a child friendly manner by opening with a kinesthetic activity to place the -ir, -er, -or words they're given in the appropriate spot at the front of the room. Students listen to a model of these vowels being stated and are asked to identify them in sentences. Appropriate time is alotted for teacher directed instruction and student practice after teacher delivers think aloud.
fsot_sp_notes: Most students actively participate in the context of the lesson during the teachers think aloud by assisting the teacher with fixing the sentence that contains r controlled vowels using the "c-o-p-s" checklist (capitilization, organization, punctuation, and spelling). Students then employ that checklist to fix the sentence "“i go tothe norse when I am HurT” on a pre-prepared worksheet and make their edits via crayon independently.
fsot_ad_notes: Teacher collects informal data by employing a # of CFUs during her think aloud. These included What two words did we spell wrong? I have a -ar what should it be if I’m writing dirt? What’s the other words I spelled wrong? (germs) What’s the letter that I need to take out and fix? How can I fix garmes to germs? Teacher also circulates to supports students in using the checklist appropriately and reviews the corrections they should have made and clarifies any misconceptions for the spelling of nurse.

k12_m_learning_goal: I can find 10 more or less.
k12_m_standards: 1.NBT.C.5. Given a two-digit number, mentally find 10 more or 10 less than the number, without having to count; explain the reasoning used. Identify arithmetic patterns of 10 more and 10 less than using strategies based on place value.
k12_m_ca1a: Yes- The enacted lesson focuses only on mathematics within the grade-level/ course-level standards.

k12_m_ca1_notes: Students engage with an activity that requires them to find 10 more or less than a number, then color the coordinating grid (which will eventually form a picture). The teacher models counting on and making jumps of 10 using a hundreds chart. Student share similar strategies with no attention to place value. Students who finish early move to a partner group to play a game where they roll dice to try to get sums that have a total of 50. Counting on is used by the majority of students.

k12_m_ca2b: 2- Student solution methods are shared, but few connections are made to strengthen student understanding.

k12_m_ca2_notes: Instruction focuses on procedures for getting the answer (counting on or using the number chart). The teacher poses questions to the class: "Who wants to show me their strategy? What can I do to get 10 more?" Students respond with the procedures (counting on, number chart); however, there is no discussion around the value of digits and what it would mean to add 10 more or have 10 less. Although students share responses, the focus is on the sum of the two numbers but there are no connections made between strategies.

k12_math_1: Unit 8 Lesson 9 Interpreting the Mean as Fair Share
k12_m_learning_goal:
Comprehend the words “mean” and “average” as a measure of center that summarizes the data using a single number.

Explain (using words and other representations) how to calculate the mean for a numerical data set.

Interpret diagrams that represent finding the mean as a process of leveling out the data to find a “fair share.”
k12_m_standards:
6.SP.A.3 Recognize that a measure of center for a numerical data set summarizes all of its values with a single number, while a measure of variation describes how its values vary with a single number.
6.SP.B Summarize and describe distributions.
6.SP.B.5.c Giving quantitative measures of center (median and/or mean) and variability (interquartile range and/or mean absolute deviation), as well as describing any overall pattern and any striking deviations from the overall pattern with reference to the context in which the data were gathered.
k12_m_ca1a: Yes- The enacted lesson focuses only on mathematics within the grade-level/ course-level standards.
k12_m_ca1b: Yes- The enacted lesson builds on students’ prior skills and understandings.
k12_m_ca1c: Yes- The enacted lesson explicitly targets the aspect(s) of Rigor called for by the standard(s) being addressed.
k12_m_ca2a: 3- Examples are used to make the mathematics of the lesson clear.
k12_m_ca2b: 3- Student solution methods are shared, and some mathematical connections are made between them.
k12_m_ca2c: 4- There are checks for understanding used throughout the lesson to assess progress of all students, and adjustments to instruction are made in response, as needed.
k12_m_ca2d: 2- The lesson includes a summary with limited focus on the mathematics.
k12_m_ca2_notes:
A: The teacher does a great job of showing students diagrams and then connects this to procedural steps to introduce the concept of mean/average. She names that student has thought about this before in equal pairs of things. 
B: The teacher actively monitors and strategically picks students to share their responses and uses the doc cam to share work. There is still room for student-to-student connection here. 
C:The teacher is skillful at creating check-ins and recalling info from previous lessons/days, and also recalls what students did during the first 30 min of Zearn. 
D: This lesson summary was rushed due to lack of time. There was a focus on the math but it was quick and in this lesson summary the teacher did not use student work to provide this summary. This is a *large* improvement from BOY :)

B: There is an opportunity for productive struggle as they always have 1-2 min of independent time, and then time to talk with their peers and use resources around the room prior to directly asking the teacher for help. 
C: The teacher implemented 3 reads for students to explain what the problem is about and then what it is asking them to do, and explain their plan prior to allowing students to just give an answer. She asks students to explain what each number means in the context of the problem. This is a bi-lingual class and the teacher always ensures students understand what the problem is talking about prior to "doing the math". She ensures students understand what each number represents and why they are doing specific operations in this lesson involving calculating the mean from a diagram/data set. 
D: There are clear protocol for students to talk to one another. The students know how to move around the room and  The teacher is clear abut what students should be talking about and what is expected of them when they come back together.

k12_m_standards: 8.EE.C.8b: Solve systems of two linear equations in two variables algebraically, and estimate solutions by graphing the equations. Solve simple cases by inspection. For example, 3x+2y=5 and 3x+2y=6 have no solution because 3x+2y cannot simultaneously be 5 and 6.

k12_m_ca2_notes:
Near the start of the lesson, the teacher explicitly models the steps to solve a system of equations while using the elimination method. As she explicitly models, she engages students by asking them guiding questions. 
“Look at the two equations. Which would you eliminate first?”
6x + 7y = 60
3x + 3y = 21
The teacher found solutions for the anticipated misconceptions and stated, “Put parentheses around everything to show that you are multiplying EACH term. Watch me multiply EACH term by -2.”
Additionally, the teacher writes a step by step guidelines on the whiteboard intended for students to follow. (Step 1 - “Make a zero pair”)

The teacher requested that students share their solution methods during class discussions. Additionally, the teacher encourages “Dennis” to share his solution method on the board with the entire class. 


As students work independently, the teacher circulates the room to assess and address misconceptions. After determining that a large portion of the class shared the same misconceptions, the teacher redirects students and explicitly teaches an entire problem. Additionally, the teacher gives individualized feedback to students. For example, she notices that a student failed to distribute a value completely and says, “Remember, we need to multiply everything. Did you multiply?”

k12_m_ca3_notes:
Immediately after modeling, the teacher prompts the students to work on independent problems. “You will work on numbers 2 and 3. Once you are done, we will review it.”

Although students were given opportunities to engage in the material, they were not given sufficient opportunities to persevere. Once students started struggling, the teacher reviewed the answers to the problem instead of offering hints to encourage them to persevere. 

The teacher asks questions and prompts students to explain their understanding of the processes. For example, “What is the first thing I will do?” “How do I make a ‘zero pair’?” “What can I multiply this by to get a zero pair?” “Why am I multiplying by -2?” “Yes, so I can cancel my Xs.” “Which operation do I need to use to eliminate this equation?” “We can multiply this, but what is another method that we could do to eliminate this equation?”

While in small groups, students discuss their solution methods with one another. However, the teacher did not carve out time in the lesson for turn and talks or small group discussions. 

While explicitly modeling, the teacher emphasizes critical vocabulary terms for this standard, including “inverse operations,” “ordered pair,” “elimination method,” etc. As students share their responses to her questions, she encourages them to use these terms.

fsot_td_notes: Teacher helps students make meaning from the text by having students tap out an unknown word, read the sentence again for fluency and then having the students read it again with more emphasis and then asks students whats happing and why was the character saying it in that manner.
